INSERT INTO `wp_posts` VALUES (1,1,'2015-08-18 15:31:49','2015-08-18 15:31:49','In this documentation I will discuss how I created a puppet module to automate the following activities :\r\n\r\n- install apache and PHP\r\n\r\n- Install MySQL\r\n\r\n- Create a database and a database user on MySQL for Wordpress\r\n\r\n- Install and configure WordPress\r\n\r\nIn order to perform these tasks I needed to spin up a ubuntu 14.04 virtual machine through AWS as well as having access to a sudo user.\r\n\r\n[embed]http://imgur.com/Mfckvyv[/embed]\r\n\r\nfirst step was to get the package downloaded using this command into the terminal via the ubuntu machine\r\n<pre class=\"code-pre \"><code>wget https://apt.puppetlabs.com/puppetlabs-release-trusty.deb\r\nsudo dpkg -i puppetlabs-release-trusty.deb</code></pre>\r\nonce this file had been downloaded I could then install puppet as well as checking the version which I had downloaded using these commands.\r\n<pre class=\"code-pre \"><code>sudo apt-get update\r\nsudo apt-get install puppet\r\n</code></pre>\r\n<pre class=\"code-pre \"><code>sudo puppet --version</code></pre>\r\nThe next stage was to install the puppet lab apache and mysql modules using the commands shown below.\r\n<pre class=\"code-pre \"><code>sudo puppet module install puppetlabs-apache\r\nsudo puppet module install puppetlabs-mysql</code></pre>\r\nonce I had completed this step I could then list the modules installed on the ubuntu machine as shown in the diagram below.\r\n\r\n[embed]http://imgur.com/zStRNq7[/embed]\r\n\r\nUpon the installation of the packages I then had to create a new directory in which I would store/create the modules. (mkdir MyModules)\r\n<pre class=\"code-pre \"><code>puppet module generate do-wordpress --skip-interview\r\n</code></pre>\r\n<pre class=\"code-pre \"><code>vi ~/MyModules/do-wordpress/metadata.json\r\n</code></pre>\r\nI then generated the modules and edited the metadata.json tag into the text editor, this has to be done because of a bug in puppet.\r\n\r\nThe next step was to start creating the manifest which would install Apache and PHP, I created the file through the \"vi\" text editor\r\n<pre class=\"code-pre \"><code>vi ~/MyModules/do-wordpress/manifests/web.pp\r\n</code></pre>\r\n<pre class=\"code-pre \"><code>class wordpress::web {\r\n\r\n    # Install Apache\r\n    class {\'apache\': \r\n        mpm_module =&gt; \'prefork\'\r\n    }\r\n\r\n    # Add support for PHP \r\n    class {\'::apache::mod::php\': }\r\n}</code></pre>\r\nin the screenshot above you can see that I added the classes as well as using a prefork via the multi-processing-module to increase compatibility with other modules.\r\n\r\nThe next step was to create a file to store configuration variables\r\n<pre class=\"code-pre \"><code>vi ~/MyModules/do-wordpress/manifests/conf.pp\r\n</code></pre>\r\n<pre class=\"code-pre \"><code>class wordpress::conf {\r\n    # You can change the values of these variables\r\n    # according to your preferences\r\n\r\n    $root_password = \'*********\'\r\n    $db_name = \'<span class=\"highlight\">wordpress</span>\'\r\n    $db_user = \'<span class=\"highlight\">wp</span>\'\r\n    $db_user_password = \'*******\'\r\n    $db_host = \'<span class=\"highlight\">localhost</span>\'\r\n\r\n    # Don\'t change the following variables\r\n\r\n    # This will evaluate to wp@localhost\r\n    $db_user_host = \"${db_user}@${db_host}\"\r\n\r\n    # This will evaluate to wp@localhost/wordpress.*\r\n    $db_user_host_db = \"${db_user}@${db_host}/${db_name}.*\"\r\n}</code></pre>\r\nAbove is the screenshot showing some of my test configuration.\r\n\r\nThe next stop was to create the manifest for MySQL, this manifest would perform the following operations;\r\n\r\n- Install the MySQL server\r\n\r\n- Sets the root password for MySQL Server\r\n\r\n- Creates a database for Wordpress\r\n\r\n- Creates a user for Wordpress\r\n\r\n- Grants privileges to the user to access the database\r\n\r\n- Install the MySQL client and bindings for various languages.\r\n<pre class=\"code-pre \"><code>class wordpress::db {\r\n\r\n    class { \'::mysql::server\':\r\n\r\n        # Set the root password\r\n        root_password =&gt; $wordpress::conf::root_password,\r\n\r\n        # Create the database\r\n        databases =&gt; {\r\n            \"${wordpress::conf::db_name}\" =&gt; {\r\n                ensure =&gt; \'present\',\r\n                charset =&gt; \'utf8\'\r\n            }\r\n        },\r\n\r\n        # Create the user\r\n        users =&gt; {\r\n            \"${wordpress::conf::db_user_host}\" =&gt; {\r\n                ensure =&gt; present,\r\n                password_hash =&gt; mysql_password(\"${wordpress::conf::db_user_password}\")\r\n            }\r\n        },\r\n\r\n        # Grant privileges to the user\r\n        grants =&gt; {\r\n            \"${wordpress::conf::db_user_host_db}\" =&gt; {\r\n                ensure     =&gt; \'present\',\r\n                options    =&gt; [\'GRANT\'],\r\n                privileges =&gt; [\'ALL\'],\r\n                table      =&gt; \"${wordpress::conf::db_name}.*\",\r\n                user       =&gt; \"${wordpress::conf::db_user_host}\",\r\n            }\r\n        },\r\n    }\r\n\r\n    # Install MySQL client and all bindings\r\n    class { \'::mysql::client\':\r\n        require =&gt; Class[\'::mysql::server\'],\r\n        bindings_enable =&gt; true\r\n    }\r\n}</code></pre>\r\nAll of the operations are performed through the classes ::mysql::server &amp; ::mysql::client\r\n\r\nThe following step is simply to download the latest version of Wordpress, in order to do this I had to create a new file in the directory \"MyModules\" this file was to be called files\r\n<pre class=\"code-pre \"><code>wget http://wordpress.org/latest.tar.gz</code></pre>\r\nabove is the command to download the latest Wordpress.\r\n\r\nThe next step was to create a template for the wp-config.php file, again I created a new file which I added to the do-wordpress folder, this file is named templates. I then moved in the /tmp folder and extracted the latest Wordpress files.\r\n<pre class=\"code-pre \"><code>tar -xvzf ~/MyModules/do-wordpress/files/latest.tar.gz  # Extract the tar\r\n</code></pre>\r\n<pre class=\"code-pre \"><code>cp /tmp/wordpress/wp-config-sample.php ~/MyModules/do-wordpress/templates/wp-config.php.erb\r\n</code></pre>\r\nI then cleaned up the /tmp folder\r\n<pre class=\"code-pre \"><code>rm -rf /tmp/wordpress  # Clean up\r\n</code></pre>\r\n<pre class=\"code-pre \"><code>vi ~/MyModules/do-wordpress/templates/wp-config.php.erb\r\n</code></pre>\r\nI then edited the wp-config.php.erb file.\r\n<pre class=\"code-pre \"><code>&lt;?php\r\ndefine(\'DB_NAME\', \'<span class=\"highlight\">&lt;%= scope.lookupvar(\'wordpress::conf::db_name\') %&gt;</span>\');\r\ndefine(\'DB_USER\', \'<span class=\"highlight\">&lt;%= scope.lookupvar(\'wordpress::conf::db_user\') %&gt;</span>\');\r\ndefine(\'DB_PASSWORD\', \'<span class=\"highlight\">&lt;%= scope.lookupvar(\'wordpress::conf::db_user_password\') %&gt;</span>\');\r\ndefine(\'DB_HOST\', \'<span class=\"highlight\">&lt;%= scope.lookupvar(\'wordpress::conf::db_host\') %&gt;</span>\');\r\ndefine(\'DB_CHARSET\', \'utf8\');\r\ndefine(\'DB_COLLATE\', \'\');\r\n\r\ndefine(\'AUTH_KEY\',         \'put your unique phrase here\');\r\ndefine(\'SECURE_AUTH_KEY\',  \'put your unique phrase here\');\r\ndefine(\'LOGGED_IN_KEY\',    \'put your unique phrase here\');\r\ndefine(\'NONCE_KEY\',        \'put your unique phrase here\');\r\ndefine(\'AUTH_SALT\',        \'put your unique phrase here\');\r\ndefine(\'SECURE_AUTH_SALT\', \'put your unique phrase here\');\r\ndefine(\'LOGGED_IN_SALT\',   \'put your unique phrase here\');\r\ndefine(\'NONCE_SALT\',       \'put your unique phrase here\');\r\n\r\n$table_prefix  = \'wp_\';\r\n\r\ndefine(\'WP_DEBUG\', false);\r\n\r\nif ( !defined(\'ABSPATH\') )\r\n    define(\'ABSPATH\', dirname(__FILE__) . \'/\');\r\n\r\nrequire_once(ABSPATH . \'wp-settings.php\');</code></pre>\r\nthe next step was to create the manifest for Wordpress\r\n<pre class=\"code-pre \"><code>vi ~/MyModules/do-wordpress/manifests/wp.pp\r\n</code></pre>\r\nI created this manifest to perform the following operations;\r\n\r\n- copy the contents of the Wordpress installation bundle to /var/www/ - this has to be done as apache has a default configuration which serves files to /var/www/\r\n\r\n- Generates the wp-config.php file using a template.\r\n<pre class=\"code-pre \"><code>class wordpress::wp {\r\n\r\n    # Copy the Wordpress bundle to /tmp\r\n    file { \'/tmp/latest.tar.gz\':\r\n        ensure =&gt; present,\r\n        source =&gt; \"puppet:///modules/wordpress/latest.tar.gz\"\r\n    }\r\n\r\n    # Extract the Wordpress bundle\r\n    exec { \'extract\':\r\n        cwd =&gt; \"/tmp\",\r\n        command =&gt; \"tar -xvzf latest.tar.gz\",\r\n        require =&gt; File[\'/tmp/latest.tar.gz\'],\r\n        path =&gt; [\'/bin\'],\r\n    }\r\n\r\n    # Copy to /var/www/\r\n    exec { \'copy\':\r\n        command =&gt; \"cp -r /tmp/wordpress/* /var/www/\",\r\n        require =&gt; Exec[\'extract\'],\r\n        path =&gt; [\'/bin\'],\r\n    }\r\n\r\n    # Generate the wp-config.php file using the template\r\n    file { \'/var/www/wp-config.php\':\r\n        ensure =&gt; present,\r\n        require =&gt; Exec[\'copy\'],\r\n        content =&gt; template(\"wordpress/wp-config.php.erb\")\r\n    }\r\n}</code></pre>\r\nthe next step was to create a .init.pp file, a manifest that integrates the other manifests.\r\n<pre class=\"code-pre \"><code>vi ~/MyModules/do-wordpress/manifests/init.pp\r\n</code></pre>\r\nthis is the code to enter into the text editor to alter the init.pp file.\r\n<pre class=\"code-pre \"><code>class wordpress {\r\n    # Load all variables\r\n    class { \'wordpress::conf\': }\r\n\r\n    # Install Apache and PHP\r\n    class { \'wordpress::web\': }\r\n\r\n    # Install MySQL\r\n    class { \'wordpress::db\': }\r\n\r\n    # Run Wordpress installation only after Apache is installed\r\n    class { \'wordpress::wp\': \r\n        require =&gt; Notify[\'Apache Installation Complete\']\r\n    }\r\n\r\n    # Display this message after MySQL installation is complete\r\n    notify { \'MySQL Installation Complete\':\r\n        require =&gt; Class[\'wordpress::db\']\r\n    }\r\n\r\n    # Display this message after Apache installation is complete\r\n    notify { \'Apache Installation Complete\':\r\n        require =&gt; Class[\'wordpress::web\']\r\n    }\r\n\r\n    # Display this message after Wordpress installation is complete\r\n    notify { \'Wordpress Installation Complete\':\r\n        require =&gt; Class[\'wordpress::wp\']\r\n    }\r\n}</code></pre>\r\nYou can see comments (#) about what each operation performs in the screenshot above.\r\n\r\nThe next step was to build the Wordpress module, this initial task i did was to change directory back to the \"MyModules\" folder, from here I then performed the following command.\r\n<pre class=\"code-pre \"><code>sudo puppet module build do-wordpress\r\n</code></pre>\r\nthis command built the Wordpress module. when entering this command I received the following message.\r\n<pre class=\"code-pre \"><code>Notice: Building /home/user/MyModules/do-wordpress for release\r\nModule built: /home/user/MyModules/do-wordpress/pkg/do-wordpress-0.1.0.tar.gz</code></pre>\r\nOnce I had built the Wordpress module I then began to install it using the following command.\r\n<pre class=\"code-pre \"><code>sudo puppet module install ~/MyModules/do-wordpress/pkg/do-wordpress-0.1.0.tar.gz\r\n</code></pre>\r\nTo test that the everything worked correctly I decided to use the module in a standalone manifest file to install Wordpress, to do this I entered the text editor for the appropriate file.\r\n<pre class=\"code-pre \"><code>vi /tmp/install-wp.pp\r\n</code></pre>\r\nI made the correct alterations to the file and then ran a puppet apply command.\r\n<pre class=\"code-pre \"><code>class { \'wordpress\':\r\n}</code></pre>\r\n<pre class=\"code-pre \"><code>sudo puppet apply /tmp/install-wp.pp</code></pre>\r\nOnce this was complete I then ran the IP address into the URL which then gave me access to the Wordpress service which we now use to document each task that we have done during the course of the DevOps case study 2015.\r\n\r\nThe final stage was to then add my team as users so that they could also document what they had done as part of the team, I assigned them all administrative roles so that they had full access to whatever they needed.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;','Setting up a Puppet module to automate activities','','publish','open','open','','hello-world','','','2015-08-20 11:12:21','2015-08-20 11:12:21','',0,'http://52.19.82.119/?p=1',0,'post','',1),(2,1,'2015-08-18 15:31:49','2015-08-18 15:31:49','This is an example page. It\'s different from a blog post because it will stay in one place and will show up in your site navigation (in most themes). Most people start with an About page that introduces them to potential site visitors. It might say something like this:\n\n<blockquote>Hi there! I\'m a bike messenger by day, aspiring actor by night, and this is my blog. I live in Los Angeles, have a great dog named Jack, and I like pi&#241;a coladas. (And gettin\' caught in the rain.)</blockquote>\n\n...or something like this:\n\n<blockquote>The XYZ Doohickey Company was founded in 1971, and has been providing quality doohickeys to the public ever since. Located in Gotham City, XYZ employs over 2,000 people and does all kinds of awesome things for the Gotham community.</blockquote>\n\nAs a new WordPress user, you should go to <a href=\"http://52.19.82.119/wp-admin/\">your dashboard</a> to delete this page and create new pages for your content. Have fun!','Sample Page','','publish','open','open','','sample-page','','','2015-08-18 15:31:49','2015-08-18 15:31:49','',0,'http://52.19.82.119/?page_id=2',0,'page','',0),(3,1,'2015-08-18 15:32:09','0000-00-00 00:00:00','','Auto Draft','','auto-draft','open','open','','','','','2015-08-18 15:32:09','0000-00-00 00:00:00','',0,'http://52.19.82.119/?p=3',0,'post','',0),(4,5,'2015-08-18 15:45:36','0000-00-00 00:00:00','','Auto Draft','','auto-draft','open','open','','','','','2015-08-18 15:45:36','0000-00-00 00:00:00','',0,'http://52.19.82.119/?p=4',0,'post','',0),(5,9,'2015-08-18 15:56:07','0000-00-00 00:00:00','','Auto Draft','','auto-draft','open','open','','','','','2015-08-18 15:56:07','0000-00-00 00:00:00','',0,'http://52.19.82.119/?p=5',0,'post','',0),(6,2,'2015-08-18 15:58:24','0000-00-00 00:00:00','','Auto Draft','','auto-draft','open','open','','','','','2015-08-18 15:58:24','0000-00-00 00:00:00','',0,'http://52.19.82.119/?p=6',0,'post','',0),(7,7,'2015-08-18 15:58:33','0000-00-00 00:00:00','','Auto Draft','','auto-draft','open','open','','','','','2015-08-18 15:58:33','0000-00-00 00:00:00','',0,'http://52.19.82.119/?p=7',0,'post','',0),(8,9,'2015-08-18 22:13:35','2015-08-18 22:13:35','A core part of our overall system design is the Continuous Delivery pipeline, the primary software tools used being Jenkins and Amazon Web Services CodeDeploy. The overall aim of implementing these technologies was to allow for Continuous Deployment through linking remote GitHub repositories to a Jenkins server which builds the code, tests it, and – assuming these tests pass – instigates CodeDeploy to deploy the new build across the relevant AWS instances.\r\n\r\n<img class=\"alignnone\" src=\"http://i.imgur.com/ZInjSkH.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"2550\" height=\"1372\" />\r\n\r\nBilal and myself were responsible for this section of the project, and the first step in this process was to manually configure Jenkins. This helped us get a better understanding of how the software worked, and laid the foundations for a largely automated process later. Ubuntu 14.04 was the platform for this server, and setting up the CI platform necessitated installing Jenkins, git plugins, JDK7, maven and also apache2 (not necessary, but useful for enabling us to proxy Jenkins through to port 80 and using the public DNS, making the Jenkins interface accessible through the world wide web with a domain name assigned by Amazon). Lots of configurations needed to be made through the Jenkins interface, for example configuring the <em>MAVEN HOME</em> location so that the developer’s Java app could be built with Jenkins. Importantly, considering the globally accessible nature of this server, security configurations were made so that anonymous users have read only access and an administrator login allows for full privileges.\r\n\r\nA crucial requirement for facilitating this build was to link the relevant GitHub repository to the Jenkins server. Firstly, an SSH key was generated for the ‘jenkins’ user on the Jenkins server, which was used as a Deploy Key for the specific repository, a measure that was implemented through the settings in GitHub. This authentication was confirmed through the command line on the Jenkins server, as shown below.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>jenkins@ip-172-31-37-36:/usr/share/maven$ ssh-keygen</em>\r\n<em>Generating public/private rsa key pair.</em>\r\n<em>Enter file in which to save the key (/var/lib/jenkins/.ssh/id_rsa):</em>\r\n<em>Created directory \'/var/lib/jenkins/.ssh\'.</em>\r\n<em>Enter passphrase (empty for no passphrase):</em>\r\n<em>Enter same passphrase again:</em>\r\n<em>Your identification has been saved in /var/lib/jenkins/.ssh/id_rsa.</em>\r\n<em>Your public key has been saved in /var/lib/jenkins/.ssh/id_rsa.pub.</em>\r\n<em>The key fingerprint is:</em>\r\n<em>de:08:ce:0a:ee:a7:d4:d6:29:68:70:29:ee:14:6a:a9 jenkins@ip-172-31-37-36</em>\r\n<em>The key\'s randomart image is:</em>\r\n<em>+--[ RSA 2048]----+</em>\r\n<em>|                            |</em>\r\n<em>|                            |</em>\r\n<em>|                            |</em>\r\n<em>|    .                       |</em>\r\n<em>|o.o     .  S             |</em>\r\n<em>|o+oo + + o          |</em>\r\n<em>|.== + = o .            |</em>\r\n<em>|=+ o.o                  |</em>\r\n<em>|Eo+o.                   |</em>\r\n<em>+-----------------------+</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>jenkins@ip-172-31-37-36:/usr/share/maven$ ssh git@github.com</em>\r\n<em>PTY allocation request failed on channel 0</em>\r\n<em>Hi AKerr94/jenkins-test! You\'ve successfully authenticated, but GitHub does not provide shell access.</em>\r\n<em>Connection to github.com closed.</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nWith the Deploy Key successfully associated, the next measure we took was to setup a webhook. This means that an action on GitHub (such as a push to the repository) triggers an action, sending this information to the Jenkins server so that it can act appropriately (in our case we did indeed want Jenkins to automatically trigger a build following a push to the linked repository). This had to be setup in the repository’s settings with special links that Jenkins could handle, and on the Jenkins side the GitHub repository had to be linked along with authorization tokens for the associated account. Linking Jenkins and GitHub like this is a little more complex than other methods but doing so in this way means that Jenkins can build from a private repository, which is beneficial for example if developers do not want their code to be made public. Successful builds will need to trigger AWS CodeDeploy to deploy the application across our instances, and failed builds are logged, with monitoring available through the Jenkins interface and dashboards giving an overview of build health and allowing for an audit trail that can be used for error troubleshooting.\r\n\r\n<img class=\"alignnone\" src=\"http://i.imgur.com/DKPyFwU.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"2548\" height=\"1170\" />\r\n\r\nIn the case of a build failure Jenkins can also be configured to notify administrators or specific email accounts (such as the developer whose build is broken!). We tested this functionality with an email address for our team.\r\n\r\n<img class=\"alignnone\" src=\"http://i.imgur.com/33WFchd.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"1826\" height=\"928\" />\r\n\r\nWe tested that this configuration was working properly, as shown below.\r\n\r\n<img class=\"alignnone\" src=\"http://i.imgur.com/GrPYT9P.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"1652\" height=\"292\" />\r\n\r\nWith the Continuous Integration portion of the setup working, we then worked on automating the process. After initial issues with Puppet configurations, and, considering that we were already using the advanced options of AWS to provision Jenkins on our initial test servers with bash scripts, we decided to extend these with a more involved and all-round script that provisioned a Jenkins server pre-configured with many of the necessary plugins and setup options, for example dynamically inputting the initiated instances public DNS into the Apache configuration in order to allow for access over the web through the Amazon hostname (otherwise this would simply lead to the Apache default splashpage on port 80 rather than redirecting to the Jenkins interface).\r\n\r\n<img class=\"alignnone\" src=\"http://i.imgur.com/Yce5rxu.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"1532\" height=\"1010\" />\r\n\r\nWith this bash script a Jenkins server can be provisioned extremely quickly with AWS, and serves as a possible route for backup/ disaster recovery in the event of a server failure, although our main disaster recovery mechanism for the Jenkins server comes in the form of an AMI created from this final server configuration, which can be deployed as an AWS instance as needed. Therefore, this AMI would be our first port of call in the event of server failure, but with the bash script we have redundancy, so, for example, were AWS to fail, or, should we want to switch to a different service, we would not be reliant on these services and could provision another server with another provider.\r\n\r\nThe next steps we will take will be to setup CodeDeploy and connect this to Jenkins, so that successful builds will be automatically deployed across our infrastructure. In this manner, we will have achieved Continuous Deployment as pushes to the GitHub repository will initiate Jenkins builds that, if successful, will update existing instances with the new code/ applications.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nAlastair Kerr &amp; Bilal Hussain','Continuous Integration with Jenkins and GitHub','','publish','open','open','','continuous-integration-with-jenkins-and-github','','','2015-08-20 09:18:25','2015-08-20 09:18:25','',0,'http://52.19.82.119/?p=8',0,'post','',0),(9,9,'2015-08-18 22:13:35','2015-08-18 22:13:35','A core part of our overall system design is the Continuous Integration pipeline, the primary software tools used being Jenkins and Amazon Web Services CodeDeploy. The overall aim of implementing these technologies was to allow for Continuous Deployment through linking remote GitHub repositories to a Jenkins server which builds the code, tests it, and – assuming these tests pass – instigates CodeDeploy to deploy the new build across the relevant AWS instances.\r\n\r\n<img class=\"alignnone\" src=\"http://i.imgur.com/ZInjSkH.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"2550\" height=\"1372\" />\r\n\r\nBilal and myself were responsible for this section of the project, and the first step in this process was to manually configure Jenkins. This helped us get a better understanding of how the software worked, and laid the foundations for a largely automated process later. Ubuntu 14.04 was the platform for this server, and setting up the CI platform necessitated installing Jenkins, git plugins, JDK7, maven and also apache2 (not necessary, but useful for enabling us to proxy Jenkins through to port 80 and using the public DNS, making the Jenkins interface accessible through the world wide web with a domain name assigned by Amazon). Lots of configurations needed to be made through the Jenkins interface, for example configuring the <em>MAVEN HOME</em> location so that the developer’s Java app could be built with Jenkins. Importantly, considering the globally accessible nature of this server, security configurations were made so that anonymous users have read only access and an administrator login allows for full privileges.\r\n\r\nA crucial requirement for facilitating this build was to link the relevant GitHub repository to the Jenkins server. Firstly, an SSH key was generated for the ‘jenkins’ user on the Jenkins server, which was used as a Deploy Key for the specific repository, a measure that was implemented through the settings in GitHub. This authentication was confirmed through the command line on the Jenkins server, as shown below.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>jenkins@ip-172-31-37-36:/usr/share/maven$ ssh-keygen</em>\r\n\r\n<em>Generating public/private rsa key pair.</em>\r\n\r\n<em>Enter file in which to save the key (/var/lib/jenkins/.ssh/id_rsa):</em>\r\n\r\n<em>Created directory \'/var/lib/jenkins/.ssh\'.</em>\r\n\r\n<em>Enter passphrase (empty for no passphrase):</em>\r\n\r\n<em>Enter same passphrase again:</em>\r\n\r\n<em>Your identification has been saved in /var/lib/jenkins/.ssh/id_rsa.</em>\r\n\r\n<em>Your public key has been saved in /var/lib/jenkins/.ssh/id_rsa.pub.</em>\r\n\r\n<em>The key fingerprint is:</em>\r\n\r\n<em>de:08:ce:0a:ee:a7:d4:d6:29:68:70:29:ee:14:6a:a9 jenkins@ip-172-31-37-36</em>\r\n\r\n<em>The key\'s randomart image is:</em>\r\n\r\n<em>+--[ RSA 2048]----+</em>\r\n\r\n<em>|                 |</em>\r\n\r\n<em>|                 |</em>\r\n\r\n<em>|                 |</em>\r\n\r\n<em>|   .             |</em>\r\n\r\n<em>|o.o   . S       |</em>\r\n\r\n<em>|o+oo + + o       |</em>\r\n\r\n<em>|.== + = o .     |</em>\r\n\r\n<em>|=+ o.o           |</em>\r\n\r\n<em>|Eo+o.           |</em>\r\n\r\n<em>+-----------------+</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>jenkins@ip-172-31-37-36:/usr/share/maven$ ssh git@github.com</em>\r\n\r\n<em>PTY allocation request failed on channel 0</em>\r\n\r\n<em>Hi AKerr94/jenkins-test! You\'ve successfully authenticated, but GitHub does not provide shell access.</em>\r\n\r\n<em>Connection to github.com closed.</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nWith the Deploy Key successfully associated, the next measure we took was to setup a webhook. This means that an action on GitHub (such as a push to the repository) triggers an action, sending this information to the Jenkins server so that it can act appropriately (in our case we did indeed want Jenkins to automatically trigger a build following a push to the linked repository). This had to be setup in the repository’s settings with special links that Jenkins could handle, and on the Jenkins side the GitHub repository had to be linked along with authorization tokens for the associated account. Linking Jenkins and GitHub like this is a little more complex than other methods but doing so in this way means that Jenkins can build from a private repository, which is beneficial for example if developers do not want their code to be made public.\r\n\r\nWith the Continuous Integration portion of the setup working, we then worked on automating the process. After initial issues with Puppet configurations, and, considering that we were already using the advanced options of AWS to provision Jenkins on our initial test servers with bash scripts, we decided to extend these with a more involved and all-round script that provisioned a Jenkins server pre-configured with many of the necessary plugins and setup options, for example dynamically inputting the initiated instances public DNS into the Apache configuration in order to allow for access over the web through the Amazon hostname (otherwise this would simply lead to the Apache default splashpage on port 80 rather than redirecting to the Jenkins interface).\r\n\r\nWith this bash script a Jenkins server can be provisioned extremely quickly with AWS, and serves as a possible route for backup/ disaster recovery in the event of a server failure, although our main disaster recovery mechanism for the Jenkins server comes in the form of an AMI created from this final server configuration, which can be deployed as an AWS instance as needed. Therefore, this AMI would be our first port of call in the event of server failure, but with the bash script we have redundancy, so, for example, were AWS to fail, or, should we want to switch to a different service, we would not be reliant on these services and could provision another server with another provider.\r\n\r\nThe next steps we will take will be to setup CodeDeploy and connect this to Jenkins, so that successful builds will be automatically deployed across our infrastructure. In this manner, we will have achieved Continuous Deployment as pushes to the GitHub repository will initiate Jenkins builds that, if successful, will update existing instances with the new code/ applications.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nAlastair Kerr &amp; Bilal Hussein','Continuous Integration with Jenkins and GitHub','','inherit','open','open','','8-revision-v1','','','2015-08-18 22:13:35','2015-08-18 22:13:35','',8,'http://52.19.82.119/index.php/2015/08/18/8-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(10,9,'2015-08-20 09:18:20','2015-08-20 09:18:20','A core part of our overall system design is the Continuous Delivery pipeline, the primary software tools used being Jenkins and Amazon Web Services CodeDeploy. The overall aim of implementing these technologies was to allow for Continuous Deployment through linking remote GitHub repositories to a Jenkins server which builds the code, tests it, and – assuming these tests pass – instigates CodeDeploy to deploy the new build across the relevant AWS instances.\n\n<img class=\"alignnone\" src=\"http://i.imgur.com/ZInjSkH.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"2550\" height=\"1372\" />\n\nBilal and myself were responsible for this section of the project, and the first step in this process was to manually configure Jenkins. This helped us get a better understanding of how the software worked, and laid the foundations for a largely automated process later. Ubuntu 14.04 was the platform for this server, and setting up the CI platform necessitated installing Jenkins, git plugins, JDK7, maven and also apache2 (not necessary, but useful for enabling us to proxy Jenkins through to port 80 and using the public DNS, making the Jenkins interface accessible through the world wide web with a domain name assigned by Amazon). Lots of configurations needed to be made through the Jenkins interface, for example configuring the <em>MAVEN HOME</em> location so that the developer’s Java app could be built with Jenkins. Importantly, considering the globally accessible nature of this server, security configurations were made so that anonymous users have read only access and an administrator login allows for full privileges.\n\nA crucial requirement for facilitating this build was to link the relevant GitHub repository to the Jenkins server. Firstly, an SSH key was generated for the ‘jenkins’ user on the Jenkins server, which was used as a Deploy Key for the specific repository, a measure that was implemented through the settings in GitHub. This authentication was confirmed through the command line on the Jenkins server, as shown below.\n\n&nbsp;\n\n<em>jenkins@ip-172-31-37-36:/usr/share/maven$ ssh-keygen</em>\n<em>Generating public/private rsa key pair.</em>\n<em>Enter file in which to save the key (/var/lib/jenkins/.ssh/id_rsa):</em>\n<em>Created directory \'/var/lib/jenkins/.ssh\'.</em>\n<em>Enter passphrase (empty for no passphrase):</em>\n<em>Enter same passphrase again:</em>\n<em>Your identification has been saved in /var/lib/jenkins/.ssh/id_rsa.</em>\n<em>Your public key has been saved in /var/lib/jenkins/.ssh/id_rsa.pub.</em>\n<em>The key fingerprint is:</em>\n<em>de:08:ce:0a:ee:a7:d4:d6:29:68:70:29:ee:14:6a:a9 jenkins@ip-172-31-37-36</em>\n<em>The key\'s randomart image is:</em>\n<em>+--[ RSA 2048]----+</em>\n<em>|                            |</em>\n<em>|                            |</em>\n<em>|                            |</em>\n<em>|    .                       |</em>\n<em>|o.o     .  S             |</em>\n<em>|o+oo + + o          |</em>\n<em>|.== + = o .            |</em>\n<em>|=+ o.o                  |</em>\n<em>|Eo+o.                   |</em>\n<em>+-----------------------+</em>\n\n&nbsp;\n\n<em>jenkins@ip-172-31-37-36:/usr/share/maven$ ssh git@github.com</em>\n<em>PTY allocation request failed on channel 0</em>\n<em>Hi AKerr94/jenkins-test! You\'ve successfully authenticated, but GitHub does not provide shell access.</em>\n<em>Connection to github.com closed.</em>\n\n&nbsp;\n\nWith the Deploy Key successfully associated, the next measure we took was to setup a webhook. This means that an action on GitHub (such as a push to the repository) triggers an action, sending this information to the Jenkins server so that it can act appropriately (in our case we did indeed want Jenkins to automatically trigger a build following a push to the linked repository). This had to be setup in the repository’s settings with special links that Jenkins could handle, and on the Jenkins side the GitHub repository had to be linked along with authorization tokens for the associated account. Linking Jenkins and GitHub like this is a little more complex than other methods but doing so in this way means that Jenkins can build from a private repository, which is beneficial for example if developers do not want their code to be made public. Successful builds will need to trigger AWS CodeDeploy to deploy the application across our instances, and failed builds are logged, with monitoring available through the Jenkins interface and dashboards giving an overview of build health and allowing for an audit trail that can be used for error troubleshooting.\n\n<img class=\"alignnone\" src=\"http://i.imgur.com/DKPyFwU.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"2548\" height=\"1170\" />\n\nIn the case of a build failure Jenkins can also be configured to notify administrators or specific email accounts (such as the developer whose build is broken!). We tested this functionality with an email address for our team.\n\n<img class=\"alignnone\" src=\"http://i.imgur.com/33WFchd.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"1826\" height=\"928\" />\n\nWe tested that this configuration was working properly, as shown below.\n\n<img class=\"alignnone\" src=\"http://i.imgur.com/GrPYT9P.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"1652\" height=\"292\" />\n\nWith the Continuous Integration portion of the setup working, we then worked on automating the process. After initial issues with Puppet configurations, and, considering that we were already using the advanced options of AWS to provision Jenkins on our initial test servers with bash scripts, we decided to extend these with a more involved and all-round script that provisioned a Jenkins server pre-configured with many of the necessary plugins and setup options, for example dynamically inputting the initiated instances public DNS into the Apache configuration in order to allow for access over the web through the Amazon hostname (otherwise this would simply lead to the Apache default splashpage on port 80 rather than redirecting to the Jenkins interface).\n\n<img class=\"alignnone\" src=\"http://i.imgur.com/Yce5rxu.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"1532\" height=\"1010\" />\n\nWith this bash script a Jenkins server can be provisioned extremely quickly with AWS, and serves as a possible route for backup/ disaster recovery in the event of a server failure, although our main disaster recovery mechanism for the Jenkins server comes in the form of an AMI created from this final server configuration, which can be deployed as an AWS instance as needed. Therefore, this AMI would be our first port of call in the event of server failure, but with the bash script we have redundancy, so, for example, were AWS to fail, or, should we want to switch to a different service, we would not be reliant on these services and could provision another server with another provider.\n\nThe next steps we will take will be to setup CodeDeploy and connect this to Jenkins, so that successful builds will be automatically deployed across our infrastructure. In this manner, we will have achieved Continuous Deployment as pushes to the GitHub repository will initiate Jenkins builds that, if successful, will update existing instances with the new code/ applications.\n\n&nbsp;\n\nAlastair Kerr &amp; Bilal Hussain','Continuous Integration with Jenkins and GitHub','','inherit','open','open','','8-autosave-v1','','','2015-08-20 09:18:20','2015-08-20 09:18:20','',8,'http://52.19.82.119/index.php/2015/08/18/8-autosave-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(11,9,'2015-08-18 22:16:36','2015-08-18 22:16:36','A core part of our overall system design is the Continuous Integration pipeline, the primary software tools used being Jenkins and Amazon Web Services CodeDeploy. The overall aim of implementing these technologies was to allow for Continuous Deployment through linking remote GitHub repositories to a Jenkins server which builds the code, tests it, and – assuming these tests pass – instigates CodeDeploy to deploy the new build across the relevant AWS instances.\r\n\r\n<img class=\"alignnone\" src=\"http://i.imgur.com/ZInjSkH.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"2550\" height=\"1372\" />\r\n\r\nBilal and myself were responsible for this section of the project, and the first step in this process was to manually configure Jenkins. This helped us get a better understanding of how the software worked, and laid the foundations for a largely automated process later. Ubuntu 14.04 was the platform for this server, and setting up the CI platform necessitated installing Jenkins, git plugins, JDK7, maven and also apache2 (not necessary, but useful for enabling us to proxy Jenkins through to port 80 and using the public DNS, making the Jenkins interface accessible through the world wide web with a domain name assigned by Amazon). Lots of configurations needed to be made through the Jenkins interface, for example configuring the <em>MAVEN HOME</em> location so that the develope