rther with Scott.\r\n\r\nJames\r\n\r\nSpent a lot of time planning and documenting. Today James will be looking at the AWS Auto-scaling as well as working with the Launch Configurations.','Tuesday 18th August (Morning Stand-up)','','publish','open','open','','tuesday-18th-august-morning-stand-up','','','2015-08-19 08:17:51','2015-08-19 08:17:51','',0,'http://52.19.82.119/?p=12',0,'post','',0),(13,2,'2015-08-19 08:15:21','2015-08-19 08:15:21','Today we have two missing members. Michael and John.\r\n\r\nScott\r\n\r\nYesterday: I deployed the word press server and set up puppet master.\r\n\r\nToday: I am going to build the manifests for agents servers.\r\n\r\nBlockages: none\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nJames\r\n\r\nYesterday: Did the apache manifest on puppet.\r\n\r\nToday: Today working on auto-scaling and load balancer\r\n\r\nBlockage: struggled with making it more efficient\r\n\r\nBilal and Ali\r\n\r\nYesterday: we did Jenkins and automating Jenkins configuration\r\n\r\nToday: we are looking into to code deploy and getting it to work with Jenkins\r\n\r\nBlockages: Lack of resources provided and difficult documentation','Wednesday 19th August (Morning Stand-Up)','','publish','open','open','','stand-up-19082015','','','2015-08-19 08:18:40','2015-08-19 08:18:40','',0,'http://52.19.82.119/?p=13',0,'post','',0),(14,7,'2015-08-19 08:15:03','2015-08-19 08:15:03','Tuesday 18<sup>th</sup> August 2015\r\n\r\nStand Up – Morning Meeting\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\nBilal</ul>\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nYesterday, Bilal was working on the Jenkins setup. Today Bilal will be playing around with the CodeDeploy services on Amazon Web Services.\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\nJohn</ul>\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nJohn began by looking over the manifests. Also mentioned that time keeping was perhaps an issue. Today the WordPress will be finished as well as possibly configuring the RDS components.\r\n<ul>Scott</ul>\r\nA lot of time planning. Today Scott plans on setting up the Vagrant Box for the Developers testing environment. Git repositories were established yesterday as well.\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\nAli</ul>\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nWorked on Jenkins as well as a lot of planning. Figuring out manually setting up the Jenkins. Today Ali is planning to investigate the Vagrant Box further with Scott.\r\n\r\nJames\r\n\r\nSpent a lot of time planning and documenting. Today James will be looking at the AWS Auto-scaling as well as working with the Launch Configurations.','Tuesday 18th August - Morning Stand-up','','inherit','open','open','','12-revision-v1','','','2015-08-19 08:15:03','2015-08-19 08:15:03','',12,'http://52.19.82.119/index.php/2015/08/19/12-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(15,9,'2015-08-19 08:15:12','2015-08-19 08:15:12','A core part of our overall system design is the Continuous Integration pipeline, the primary software tools used being Jenkins and Amazon Web Services CodeDeploy. The overall aim of implementing these technologies was to allow for Continuous Deployment through linking remote GitHub repositories to a Jenkins server which builds the code, tests it, and – assuming these tests pass – instigates CodeDeploy to deploy the new build across the relevant AWS instances.\r\n\r\n<img class=\"alignnone\" src=\"http://i.imgur.com/ZInjSkH.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"2550\" height=\"1372\" />\r\n\r\nBilal and myself were responsible for this section of the project, and the first step in this process was to manually configure Jenkins. This helped us get a better understanding of how the software worked, and laid the foundations for a largely automated process later. Ubuntu 14.04 was the platform for this server, and setting up the CI platform necessitated installing Jenkins, git plugins, JDK7, maven and also apache2 (not necessary, but useful for enabling us to proxy Jenkins through to port 80 and using the public DNS, making the Jenkins interface accessible through the world wide web with a domain name assigned by Amazon). Lots of configurations needed to be made through the Jenkins interface, for example configuring the <em>MAVEN HOME</em> location so that the developer’s Java app could be built with Jenkins. Importantly, considering the globally accessible nature of this server, security configurations were made so that anonymous users have read only access and an administrator login allows for full privileges.\r\n\r\nA crucial requirement for facilitating this build was to link the relevant GitHub repository to the Jenkins server. Firstly, an SSH key was generated for the ‘jenkins’ user on the Jenkins server, which was used as a Deploy Key for the specific repository, a measure that was implemented through the settings in GitHub. This authentication was confirmed through the command line on the Jenkins server, as shown below.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>jenkins@ip-172-31-37-36:/usr/share/maven$ ssh-keygen</em>\r\n<em>Generating public/private rsa key pair.</em>\r\n<em>Enter file in which to save the key (/var/lib/jenkins/.ssh/id_rsa):</em>\r\n<em>Created directory \'/var/lib/jenkins/.ssh\'.</em>\r\n<em>Enter passphrase (empty for no passphrase):</em>\r\n<em>Enter same passphrase again:</em>\r\n<em>Your identification has been saved in /var/lib/jenkins/.ssh/id_rsa.</em>\r\n<em>Your public key has been saved in /var/lib/jenkins/.ssh/id_rsa.pub.</em>\r\n<em>The key fingerprint is:</em>\r\n<em>de:08:ce:0a:ee:a7:d4:d6:29:68:70:29:ee:14:6a:a9 jenkins@ip-172-31-37-36</em>\r\n<em>The key\'s randomart image is:</em>\r\n<em>+--[ RSA 2048]----+</em>\r\n<em>|                            |</em>\r\n<em>|                            |</em>\r\n<em>|                            |</em>\r\n<em>|    .                       |</em>\r\n<em>|o.o     .  S             |</em>\r\n<em>|o+oo + + o          |</em>\r\n<em>|.== + = o .            |</em>\r\n<em>|=+ o.o                  |</em>\r\n<em>|Eo+o.                   |</em>\r\n<em>+-----------------------+</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>jenkins@ip-172-31-37-36:/usr/share/maven$ ssh git@github.com</em>\r\n<em>PTY allocation request failed on channel 0</em>\r\n<em>Hi AKerr94/jenkins-test! You\'ve successfully authenticated, but GitHub does not provide shell access.</em>\r\n<em>Connection to github.com closed.</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nWith the Deploy Key successfully associated, the next measure we took was to setup a webhook. This means that an action on GitHub (such as a push to the repository) triggers an action, sending this information to the Jenkins server so that it can act appropriately (in our case we did indeed want Jenkins to automatically trigger a build following a push to the linked repository). This had to be setup in the repository’s settings with special links that Jenkins could handle, and on the Jenkins side the GitHub repository had to be linked along with authorization tokens for the associated account. Linking Jenkins and GitHub like this is a little more complex than other methods but doing so in this way means that Jenkins can build from a private repository, which is beneficial for example if developers do not want their code to be made public.\r\n\r\nWith the Continuous Integration portion of the setup working, we then worked on automating the process. After initial issues with Puppet configurations, and, considering that we were already using the advanced options of AWS to provision Jenkins on our initial test servers with bash scripts, we decided to extend these with a more involved and all-round script that provisioned a Jenkins server pre-configured with many of the necessary plugins and setup options, for example dynamically inputting the initiated instances public DNS into the Apache configuration in order to allow for access over the web through the Amazon hostname (otherwise this would simply lead to the Apache default splashpage on port 80 rather than redirecting to the Jenkins interface).\r\n\r\n<img class=\"alignnone\" src=\"http://i.imgur.com/Yce5rxu.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"1532\" height=\"1010\" />\r\n\r\nWith this bash script a Jenkins server can be provisioned extremely quickly with AWS, and serves as a possible route for backup/ disaster recovery in the event of a server failure, although our main disaster recovery mechanism for the Jenkins server comes in the form of an AMI created from this final server configuration, which can be deployed as an AWS instance as needed. Therefore, this AMI would be our first port of call in the event of server failure, but with the bash script we have redundancy, so, for example, were AWS to fail, or, should we want to switch to a different service, we would not be reliant on these services and could provision another server with another provider.\r\n\r\nThe next steps we will take will be to setup CodeDeploy and connect this to Jenkins, so that successful builds will be automatically deployed across our infrastructure. In this manner, we will have achieved Continuous Deployment as pushes to the GitHub repository will initiate Jenkins builds that, if successful, will update existing instances with the new code/ applications.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nAlastair Kerr &amp; Bilal Hussain','Continuous Integration with Jenkins and GitHub','','inherit','open','open','','8-revision-v1','','','2015-08-19 08:15:12','2015-08-19 08:15:12','',8,'http://52.19.82.119/index.php/2015/08/19/8-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(16,2,'2015-08-19 08:15:21','2015-08-19 08:15:21','Today we have two missing members. Michael and John.\r\n\r\nScott:\r\n\r\nYesterday: I deployed the word press server and set up puppet master.\r\n\r\nToday: I am going to build the manifests for agents servers.\r\n\r\nBlockages: none\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nJame:\r\n\r\nYesterday: Did the apache manifest on puppet.\r\n\r\nToday: Today working on auto-scaling and load balancer\r\n\r\nBlockage: struggled with making it more efficient\r\n\r\nBilal and Ali:\r\n\r\nYesterday: we did Jenkins and automating Jenkins configuration\r\n\r\nToday: we are looking into to code deploy and getting it to work with Jenkins\r\n\r\nBlockages: Lack of resources provided and difficult documentation','Stand UP (19/08/2015)','','inherit','open','open','','13-revision-v1','','','2015-08-19 08:15:21','2015-08-19 08:15:21','',13,'http://52.19.82.119/index.php/2015/08/19/13-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(17,2,'2015-08-19 08:15:49','2015-08-19 08:15:49','Today we have two missing members. Michael and John.\r\n\r\nScott:\r\n\r\nYesterday: I deployed the word press server and set up puppet master.\r\n\r\nToday: I am going to build the manifests for agents servers.\r\n\r\nBlockages: none\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nJames:\r\n\r\nYesterday: Did the apache manifest on puppet.\r\n\r\nToday: Today working on auto-scaling and load balancer\r\n\r\nBlockage: struggled with making it more efficient\r\n\r\nBilal and Ali:\r\n\r\nYesterday: we did Jenkins and automating Jenkins configuration\r\n\r\nToday: we are looking into to code deploy and getting it to work with Jenkins\r\n\r\nBlockages: Lack of resources provided and difficult documentation','Stand UP (19/08/2015)','','inherit','open','open','','13-revision-v1','','','2015-08-19 08:15:49','2015-08-19 08:15:49','',13,'http://52.19.82.119/index.php/2015/08/19/13-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(18,7,'2015-08-19 08:16:30','2015-08-19 08:16:30','Stand Up – Morning Meeting\r\n\r\nBilal\r\n\r\nYesterday, Bilal was working on the Jenkins setup. Today Bilal will be playing around with the CodeDeploy services on Amazon Web Services.\r\n\r\nJohn\r\n\r\nJohn began by looking over the manifests. Also mentioned that time keeping was perhaps an issue. Today the WordPress will be finished as well as possibly configuring the RDS components.\r\n\r\nScott\r\n\r\nA lot of time planning. Today Scott plans on setting up the Vagrant Box for the Developers testing environment. Git repositories were established yesterday as well.\r\n\r\nAli\r\n\r\nWorked on Jenkins as well as a lot of planning. Figuring out manually setting up the Jenkins. Today Ali is planning to investigate the Vagrant Box further with Scott.\r\n\r\nJames\r\n\r\nSpent a lot of time planning and documenting. Today James will be looking at the AWS Auto-scaling as well as working with the Launch Configurations.','Tuesday 18th August - Morning Stand-up','','inherit','open','open','','12-revision-v1','','','2015-08-19 08:16:30','2015-08-19 08:16:30','',12,'http://52.19.82.119/index.php/2015/08/19/12-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(19,7,'2015-08-19 08:17:07','2015-08-19 08:17:07','Stand Up – Morning Meeting\r\n\r\nBilal\r\n\r\nYesterday, Bilal was working on the Jenkins setup. Today Bilal will be playing around with the CodeDeploy services on Amazon Web Services.\r\n\r\nJohn\r\n\r\nJohn began by looking over the manifests. Also mentioned that time keeping was perhaps an issue. Today the WordPress will be finished as well as possibly configuring the RDS components.\r\n\r\nScott\r\n\r\nA lot of time planning. Today Scott plans on setting up the Vagrant Box for the Developers testing environment. Git repositories were established yesterday as well.\r\n\r\nAli\r\n\r\nWorked on Jenkins as well as a lot of planning. Figuring out manually setting up the Jenkins. Today Ali is planning to investigate the Vagrant Box further with Scott.\r\n\r\nJames\r\n\r\nSpent a lot of time planning and documenting. Today James will be looking at the AWS Auto-scaling as well as working with the Launch Configurations.','Tuesday 18th August (Morning Stand-up)','','inherit','open','open','','12-revision-v1','','','2015-08-19 08:17:07','2015-08-19 08:17:07','',12,'http://52.19.82.119/index.php/2015/08/19/12-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(20,7,'2015-08-19 08:17:24','2015-08-19 08:17:24','Bilal\r\n\r\nYesterday, Bilal was working on the Jenkins setup. Today Bilal will be playing around with the CodeDeploy services on Amazon Web Services.\r\n\r\nJohn\r\n\r\nJohn began by looking over the manifests. Also mentioned that time keeping was perhaps an issue. Today the WordPress will be finished as well as possibly configuring the RDS components.\r\n\r\nScott\r\n\r\nA lot of time planning. Today Scott plans on setting up the Vagrant Box for the Developers testing environment. Git repositories were established yesterday as well.\r\n\r\nAli\r\n\r\nWorked on Jenkins as well as a lot of planning. Figuring out manually setting up the Jenkins. Today Ali is planning to investigate the Vagrant Box further with Scott.\r\n\r\nJames\r\n\r\nSpent a lot of time planning and documenting. Today James will be looking at the AWS Auto-scaling as well as working with the Launch Configurations.','Tuesday 18th August (Morning Stand-up)','','inherit','open','open','','12-revision-v1','','','2015-08-19 08:17:24','2015-08-19 08:17:24','',12,'http://52.19.82.119/index.php/2015/08/19/12-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(21,7,'2015-08-19 08:18:40','2015-08-19 08:18:40','Today we have two missing members. Michael and John.\r\n\r\nScott\r\n\r\nYesterday: I deployed the word press server and set up puppet master.\r\n\r\nToday: I am going to build the manifests for agents servers.\r\n\r\nBlockages: none\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nJames\r\n\r\nYesterday: Did the apache manifest on puppet.\r\n\r\nToday: Today working on auto-scaling and load balancer\r\n\r\nBlockage: struggled with making it more efficient\r\n\r\nBilal and Ali\r\n\r\nYesterday: we did Jenkins and automating Jenkins configuration\r\n\r\nToday: we are looking into to code deploy and getting it to work with Jenkins\r\n\r\nBlockages: Lack of resources provided and difficult documentation','Wednesday 19th August (Morning Stand-Up)','','inherit','open','open','','13-revision-v1','','','2015-08-19 08:18:40','2015-08-19 08:18:40','',13,'http://52.19.82.119/index.php/2015/08/19/13-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(22,5,'2015-08-19 08:58:10','0000-00-00 00:00:00','I started the installation creating a virtual machine on my local machine and installing Ubuntu 14.04 (64 bit).\n\nI then updated the system\'s packages and installed Tomcat 6:\n\n<strong>root@ubuntu:/home/ubuntu# apt-get update</strong>\n\n<strong>root@ubuntu:/home/ubuntu# apt-get install tomcat 6</strong>\n\n&nbsp;','Installing Tomcat 6','','draft','open','open','','','','','2015-08-19 08:58:10','2015-08-19 08:58:10','',0,'http://52.19.82.119/?p=22',0,'post','',0),(23,5,'2015-08-19 09:39:30','0000-00-00 00:00:00','I started the installation creating a virtual machine on my local machine and installing Ubuntu 14.04 (64 bit).\n\nI then updated the system\'s packages and installed Tomcat 6:\n\n<strong>root@ubuntu:/home/ubuntu# apt-get update</strong>\n\n<strong>root@ubuntu:/home/ubuntu# apt-get install tomcat 6</strong>\n\nTo verify that tomcat was installed correctly, I checked that I could see the default landing page in my web browser.\n\nIMAGE 1\n\nBy default, Tomcat 6 runs on port 8080. To chance the default port for Tomcat I edited the /etc/tomcat6/server.xml file and updated the default port for http connections.\n\nIMAGE 2\n\n&nbsp;\n\n/etc/tomcat6/Catalina\n\n&nbsp;','Installing Tomcat','','draft','open','open','','','','','2015-08-19 09:39:30','2015-08-19 09:39:30','',0,'http://52.19.82.119/?p=23',0,'post','',0),(24,2,'2015-08-19 16:58:57','2015-08-19 16:58:57','<p style=\"text-align: left;\">To install code deploy, I first need to set up IAM roles and attach modified policies. The new roles are :</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li style=\"text-align: left;\">CodeDeploy</li>\r\n	<li style=\"text-align: left;\">EC2CodeDeploy</li>\r\n</ul>\r\nCode Deploy Policy:\r\n<pre>{\r\n\r\n \"Version\": \"2012-10-17\",\r\n\r\n \"Statement\": [\r\n\r\n   {\r\n\r\n     \"Action\": [\r\n\r\n       \"autoscaling:PutLifecycleHook\",\r\n\r\n       \"autoscaling:DeleteLifecycleHook\",\r\n\r\n       \"autoscaling:RecordLifecycleActionHeartbeat\",\r\n\r\n       \"autoscaling:CompleteLifecycleAction\",\r\n\r\n       \"autoscaling:DescribeAutoscalingGroups\",\r\n\r\n       \"autoscaling:PutInstanceInStandby\",\r\n\r\n       \"autoscaling:PutInstanceInService\",\r\n\r\n       \"ec2:Describe*\"\r\n\r\n     ],\r\n\r\n     \"Effect\": \"Allow\",\r\n\r\n     \"Resource\": \"*\"\r\n\r\n   }\r\n\r\n ]\r\n\r\n}\r\n\r\nOnce created, I need to edit the relationship trust by click edit relationship trust and replace the contents with the following:</pre>\r\n<pre>{\r\n\r\n \"Version\": \"2012-10-17\",\r\n\r\n \"Statement\": [\r\n\r\n   {\r\n\r\n     \"Sid\": \"\",\r\n\r\n     \"Effect\": \"Allow\",\r\n\r\n     \"Principal\": {\r\n\r\n       \"Service\": [\r\n\r\n         \"codedeploy.us-west-2.amazonaws.com\",\r\n\r\n         \"codedeploy.us-east-1.amazonaws.com\"\r\n\r\n       ]\r\n\r\n     },\r\n\r\n     \"Action\": \"sts:AssumeRole\"\r\n\r\n   }\r\n\r\n ]\r\n\r\n}\r\n\r\n\r\n</pre>\r\nRepeat the above step with EC2CodeDeploy but no need to update the trust policy. Once roles are created, launch an EC2 instance with the EC2DeployPolicy attached. In the EC2 instance, first install AWS command line. To install aws cli:\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li>Make sure python is installed by typing \"python --version\"</li>\r\n	<li>Sudo apt-get update</li>\r\n	<li>sudo apt-get install awscli</li>\r\n	<li>run aws help to check if it has installed successfully</li>\r\n</ol>\r\nThe following steps to install CodeDeploy Agent\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li>aws s3 cp s3://aws-codedeploy-eu-west-1/latest/install . --region eu-west1-1</li>\r\n	<li>chmod +x install</li>\r\n	<li>sed -i \"s/sleep(.*)/sleep(10)/\" install</li>\r\n	<li>Make sure ruby v2.0 is installed if not, run sudo apt-get install ruby2.0</li>\r\n	<li>./install auto</li>\r\n	<li>service codedeploy-agent status</li>\r\n</ol>\r\nWe ended up not using it as we did not have proper right to use code deploy service.','CodeDeploy (Documentation of progress)','','publish','open','open','','codedeploy-documentation-of-progress','','','2015-08-19 16:58:57','2015-08-19 16:58:57','',0,'http://52.19.82.119/?p=24',0,'post','',0),(25,2,'2015-08-19 09:30:09','2015-08-19 09:30:09','<p style=\"text-align: left;\">To install code deploy, I first need to set up IAM roles and attach modified policies. The new roles are :</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li style=\"text-align: left;\">CodeDeploy</li>\r\n	<li style=\"text-align: left;\">EC2CodeDeploy</li>\r\n</ul>\r\nCode Deploy Policy:\r\n<pre>{\r\n\r\n \"Version\": \"2012-10-17\",\r\n\r\n \"Statement\": [\r\n\r\n   {\r\n\r\n     \"Action\": [\r\n\r\n       \"autoscaling:PutLifecycleHook\",\r\n\r\n       \"autoscaling:DeleteLifecycleHook\",\r\n\r\n       \"autoscaling:RecordLifecycleActionHeartbeat\",\r\n\r\n       \"autoscaling:CompleteLifecycleAction\",\r\n\r\n       \"autoscaling:DescribeAutoscalingGroups\",\r\n\r\n       \"autoscaling:PutInstanceInStandby\",\r\n\r\n       \"autoscaling:PutInstanceInService\",\r\n\r\n       \"ec2:Describe*\"\r\n\r\n     ],\r\n\r\n     \"Effect\": \"Allow\",\r\n\r\n     \"Resource\": \"*\"\r\n\r\n   }\r\n\r\n ]\r\n\r\n}\r\n\r\nOnce created, I need to edit the relationship trust by click edit relationship trust and replace the contents with the following:</pre>\r\n<pre>{\r\n\r\n \"Version\": \"2012-10-17\",\r\n\r\n \"Statement\": [\r\n\r\n   {\r\n\r\n     \"Sid\": \"\",\r\n\r\n     \"Effect\": \"Allow\",\r\n\r\n     \"Principal\": {\r\n\r\n       \"Service\": [\r\n\r\n         \"codedeploy.us-west-2.amazonaws.com\",\r\n\r\n         \"codedeploy.us-east-1.amazonaws.com\"\r\n\r\n       ]\r\n\r\n     },\r\n\r\n     \"Action\": \"sts:AssumeRole\"\r\n\r\n   }\r\n\r\n ]\r\n\r\n}\r\n\r\nRepeat the above step with EC2CodeDeploy but no need to update the trust policy.\r\n\r\nOnce roles are created, launch an EC2 instance with the EC2DeployPolicy attached. \r\nIn the EC2 instance, first install AWS command line.</pre>\r\n&nbsp;','CodeDeploy','','inherit','open','open','','24-revision-v1','','','2015-08-19 09:30:09','2015-08-19 09:30:09','',24,'http://52.19.82.119/index.php/2015/08/19/24-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(26,9,'2015-08-19 10:29:54','2015-08-19 10:29:54','A core part of our overall system design is the Continuous Integration pipeline, the primary software tools used being Jenkins and Amazon Web Services CodeDeploy. The overall aim of implementing these technologies was to allow for Continuous Deployment through linking remote GitHub repositories to a Jenkins server which builds the code, tests it, and – assuming these tests pass – instigates CodeDeploy to deploy the new build across the relevant AWS instances.\r\n\r\n<img class=\"alignnone\" src=\"http://i.imgur.com/ZInjSkH.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"2550\" height=\"1372\" />\r\n\r\nBilal and myself were responsible for this section of the project, and the first step in this process was to manually configure Jenkins. This helped us get a better understanding of how the software worked, and laid the foundations for a largely automated process later. Ubuntu 14.04 was the platform for this server, and setting up the CI platform necessitated installing Jenkins, git plugins, JDK7, maven and also apache2 (not necessary, but useful for enabling us to proxy Jenkins through to port 80 and using the public DNS, making the Jenkins interface accessible through the world wide web with a domain name assigned by Amazon). Lots of configurations needed to be made through the Jenkins interface, for example configuring the <em>MAVEN HOME</em> location so that the developer’s Java app could be built with Jenkins. Importantly, considering the globally accessible nature of this server, security configurations were made so that anonymous users have read only access and an administrator login allows for full privileges.\r\n\r\nA crucial requirement for facilitating this build was to link the relevant GitHub repository to the Jenkins server. Firstly, an SSH key was generated for the ‘jenkins’ user on the Jenkins server, which was used as a Deploy Key for the specific repository, a measure that was implemented through the settings in GitHub. This authentication was confirmed through the command line on the Jenkins server, as shown below.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>jenkins@ip-172-31-37-36:/usr/share/maven$ ssh-keygen</em>\r\n<em>Generating public/private rsa key pair.</em>\r\n<em>Enter file in which to save the key (/var/lib/jenkins/.ssh/id_rsa):</em>\r\n<em>Created directory \'/var/lib/jenkins/.ssh\'.</em>\r\n<em>Enter passphrase (empty for no passphrase):</em>\r\n<em>Enter same passphrase again:</em>\r\n<em>Your identification has been saved in /var/lib/jenkins/.ssh/id_rsa.</em>\r\n<em>Your public key has been saved in /var/lib/jenkins/.ssh/id_rsa.pub.</em>\r\n<em>The key fingerprint is:</em>\r\n<em>de:08:ce:0a:ee:a7:d4:d6:29:68:70:29:ee:14:6a:a9 jenkins@ip-172-31-37-36</em>\r\n<em>The key\'s randomart image is:</em>\r\n<em>+--[ RSA 2048]----+</em>\r\n<em>|                            |</em>\r\n<em>|                            |</em>\r\n<em>|                            |</em>\r\n<em>|    .                       |</em>\r\n<em>|o.o     .  S             |</em>\r\n<em>|o+oo + + o          |</em>\r\n<em>|.== + = o .            |</em>\r\n<em>|=+ o.o                  |</em>\r\n<em>|Eo+o.                   |</em>\r\n<em>+-----------------------+</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>jenkins@ip-172-31-37-36:/usr/share/maven$ ssh git@github.com</em>\r\n<em>PTY allocation request failed on channel 0</em>\r\n<em>Hi AKerr94/jenkins-test! You\'ve successfully authenticated, but GitHub does not provide shell access.</em>\r\n<em>Connection to github.com closed.</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nWith the Deploy Key successfully associated, the next measure we took was to setup a webhook. This means that an action on GitHub (such as a push to the repository) triggers an action, sending this information to the Jenkins server so that it can act appropriately (in our case we did indeed want Jenkins to automatically trigger a build following a push to the linked repository). This had to be setup in the repository’s settings with special links that Jenkins could handle, and on the Jenkins side the GitHub repository had to be linked along with authorization tokens for the associated account. Linking Jenkins and GitHub like this is a little more complex than other methods but doing so in this way means that Jenkins can build from a private repository, which is beneficial for example if developers do not want their code to be made public. Successful builds will need to trigger AWS CodeDeploy to deploy the application across our instances, and failed builds are logged, with monitoring available through the Jenkins interface and dashboards giving an overview of build health and allowing for an audit trail that can be used for error troubleshooting.\r\n\r\n<img class=\"alignnone\" src=\"http://i.imgur.com/DKPyFwU.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"2548\" height=\"1170\" />\r\n\r\nWith the Continuous Integration portion of the setup working, we then worked on automating the process. After initial issues with Puppet configurations, and, considering that we were already using the advanced options of AWS to provision Jenkins on our initial test servers with bash scripts, we decided to extend these with a more involved and all-round script that provisioned a Jenkins server pre-configured with many of the necessary plugins and setup options, for example dynamically inputting the initiated instances public DNS into the Apache configuration in order to allow for access over the web through the Amazon hostname (otherwise this would simply lead to the Apache default splashpage on port 80 rather than redirecting to the Jenkins interface).\r\n\r\n<img class=\"alignnone\" src=\"http://i.imgur.com/Yce5rxu.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"1532\" height=\"1010\" />\r\n\r\nWith this bash script a Jenkins server can be provisioned extremely quickly with AWS, and serves as a possible route for backup/ disaster recovery in the event of a server failure, although our main disaster recovery mechanism for the Jenkins server comes in the form of an AMI created from this final server configuration, which can be deployed as an AWS instance as needed. Therefore, this AMI would be our first port of call in the event of server failure, but with the bash script we have redundancy, so, for example, were AWS to fail, or, should we want to switch to a different service, we would not be reliant on these services and could provision another server with another provider.\r\n\r\nThe next steps we will take will be to setup CodeDeploy and connect this to Jenkins, so that successful builds will be automatically deployed across our infrastructure. In this manner, we will have achieved Continuous Deployment as pushes to the GitHub repository will initiate Jenkins builds that, if successful, will update existing instances with the new code/ applications.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nAlastair Kerr &amp; Bilal Hussain','Continuous Integration with Jenkins and GitHub','','inherit','open','open','','8-revision-v1','','','2015-08-19 10:29:54','2015-08-19 10:29:54','',8,'http://52.19.82.119/index.php/2015/08/19/8-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(27,9,'2015-08-19 10:58:14','2015-08-19 10:58:14','A core part of our overall system design is the Continuous Integration pipeline, the primary software tools used being Jenkins and Amazon Web Services CodeDeploy. The overall aim of implementing these technologies was to allow for Continuous Deployment through linking remote GitHub repositories to a Jenkins server which builds the code, tests it, and – assuming these tests pass – instigates CodeDeploy to deploy the new build across the relevant AWS instances.\r\n\r\n<img class=\"alignnone\" src=\"http://i.imgur.com/ZInjSkH.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"2550\" height=\"1372\" />\r\n\r\nBilal and myself were responsible for this section of the project, and the first step in this process was to manually configure Jenkins. This helped us get a better understanding of how the software worked, and laid the foundations for a largely automated process later. Ubuntu 14.04 was the platform for this server, and setting up the CI platform necessitated installing Jenkins, git plugins, JDK7, maven and also apache2 (not necessary, but useful for enabling us to proxy Jenkins through to port 80 and using the public DNS, making the Jenkins interface accessible through the world wide web with a domain name assigned by Amazon). Lots of configurations needed to be made through the Jenkins interface, for example configuring the <em>MAVEN HOME</em> location so that the developer’s Java app could be built with Jenkins. Importantly, considering the globally accessible nature of this server, security configurations were made so that anonymous users have read only access and an administrator login allows for full privileges.\r\n\r\nA crucial requirement for facilitating this build was to link the relevant GitHub repository to the Jenkins server. Firstly, an SSH key was generated for the ‘jenkins’ user on the Jenkins server, which was used as a Deploy Key for the specific repository, a measure that was implemented through the settings in GitHub. This authentication was confirmed through the command line on the Jenkins server, as shown below.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>jenkins@ip-172-31-37-36:/usr/share/maven$ ssh-keygen</em>\r\n<em>Generating public/private rsa key pair.</em>\r\n<em>Enter file in which to save the key (/var/lib/jenkins/.ssh/id_rsa):</em>\r\n<em>Created directory \'/var/lib/jenkins/.ssh\'.</em>\r\n<em>Enter passphrase (empty for no passphrase):</em>\r\n<em>Enter same passphrase again:</em>\r\n<em>Your identification has been saved in /var/lib/jenkins/.ssh/id_rsa.</em>\r\n<em>Your public key has been saved in /var/lib/jenkins/.ssh/id_rsa.pub.</em>\r\n<em>The key fingerprint is:</em>\r\n<em>de:08:ce:0a:ee:a7:d4:d6:29:68:70:29:ee:14:6a:a9 jenkins@ip-172-31-37-36</em>\r\n<em>The key\'s randomart image is:</em>\r\n<em>+--[ RSA 2048]----+</em>\r\n<em>|                            |</em>\r\n<em>|                            |</em>\r\n<em>|                            |</em>\r\n<em>|    .                       |</em>\r\n<em>|o.o     .  S             |</em>\r\n<em>|o+oo + + o          |</em>\r\n<em>|.== + = o .            |</em>\r\n<em>|=+ o.o                  |</em>\r\n<em>|Eo+o.                   |</em>\r\n<em>+-----------------------+</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>jenkins@ip-172-31-37-36:/usr/share/maven$ ssh git@github.com</em>\r\n<em>PTY allocation request failed on channel 0</em>\r\n<em>Hi AKerr94/jenkins-test! You\'ve successfully authenticated, but GitHub does not provide shell access.</em>\r\n<em>Connection to github.com closed.</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nWith the Deploy Key successfully associated, the next measure we took was to setup a webhook. This means that an action on GitHub (such as a push to the repository) triggers an action, sending this information to the Jenkins server so that it can act appropriately (in our case we did indeed want Jenkins to automatically trigger a build following a push to the linked repository). This had to be setup in the repository’s settings with special links that Jenkins could handle, and on the Jenkins side the GitHub repository had to be linked along with authorization tokens for the associated account. Linking Jenkins and GitHub like this is a little more complex than other methods but doing so in this way means that Jenkins can build from a private repository, which is beneficial for example if developers do not want their code to be made public. Successful builds will need to trigger AWS CodeDeploy to deploy the application across our instances, and failed builds are logged, with monitoring available through the Jenkins interface and dashboards giving an overview of build health and allowing for an audit trail that can be used for error troubleshooting.\r\n\r\n<img class=\"alignnone\" src=\"http://i.imgur.com/DKPyFwU.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"2548\" height=\"1170\" />\r\n\r\nIn the case of a build failure Jenkins can also be configured to notify administrators or specific email accounts (such as the developer whose build is broken!). We tested this functionality with an email address for our team.\r\n\r\n<img class=\"alignnone\" src=\"http://i.imgur.com/JYhKt2X.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"1718\" height=\"590\" />\r\n\r\nWith the Continuous Integration portion of the setup working, we then worked on automating the process. After initial issues with Puppet configurations, and, considering that we were already using the advanced options of AWS to provision Jenkins on our initial test servers with bash scripts, we decided to extend these with a more involved and all-round script that provisioned a Jenkins server pre-configured with many of the necessary plugins and setup options, for example dynamically inputting the initiated instances public DNS into the Apache configuration in order to allow for access over the web through the Amazon hostname (otherwise this would simply lead to the Apache default splashpage on port 80 rather than redirecting to the Jenkins interface).\r\n\r\n<img class=\"alignnone\" src=\"http://i.imgur.com/Yce5rxu.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"1532\" height=\"1010\" />\r\n\r\nWith this bash script a Jenkins server can be provisioned extremely quickly with AWS, and serves as a possible route for backup/ disaster recovery in the event of a server failure, although our main disaster recovery mechanism for the Jenkins server comes in the form of an AMI created from this final server configuration, which can be deployed as an AWS instance as needed. Therefore, this AMI would be our first port of call in the event of server failure, but with the bash script we have redundancy, so, for example, were AWS to fail, or, should we want to switch to a different service, we would not be reliant on these services and could provision another server with another provider.\r\n\r\nThe next steps we will take will be to setup CodeDeploy and connect this to Jenkins, so that successful builds will be automatically deployed across our infrastructure. In this manner, we will have achieved Continuous Deployment as pushes to the GitHub repository will initiate Jenkins builds that, if successful, will update existing instances with the new code/ applications.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nAlastair Kerr &amp; Bilal Hussain','Continuous Integration with Jenkins and GitHub','','inherit','open','open','','8-revision-v1','','','2015-08-19 10:58:14','2015-08-19 10:58:14','',8,'http://52.19.82.119/index.php/2015/08/19/8-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(28,9,'2015-08-19 14:54:56','2015-08-19 14:54:56','Our initial plan was to use CodeDeploy, but after setting up the roles and profiles in AWS we found out that the Amazon accounts we had been provided with did not have access to the service. This was a big problem for us as CodeDeploy was a huge part of the Continuous Delivery pipeline and using it would have meant successful builds would swiftly and automatically be rolled out across our instances.\r\n\r\n<img class=\"alignnone\" src=\"http://i.imgur.com/Gn09XmN.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"582\" height=\"202\" />\r\n\r\nWithout this tool at our disposal we needed to find an alternative way. At this point we had fully implemented Continuous Integration with Jenkins for the Tomcat application, and so needed to work out how to get this build sent to our servers. We installed several Jenkins plugins to handle the post build steps; PostBuildScript allows for bash scripts to be executed as a post build action, and Artifact deployer allows for archived artifacts to be relocated to a more manageable location.\r\n\r\n<img class=\"alignnone\" src=\"http://i.imgur.com/fuUegLg.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"1844\" height=\"1156\" />\r\n\r\nThe specific implementation copies the archived build artifact (in the case of this Tomcat application, .war file) to a folder /builds/ owned by the Jenkins user, and then executes a simple scp transfer of the artifact to the Puppet master server (this involved configuring a limited permissions Jenkin user on the Puppet server with the public key from the Jenkins machine pasted into the authorized_keys for this new user). This meant that the Jenkins portion of the pipeline for this application was complete, with a push to the GitHub repository initiating a Jenkins build which, if successful, automatically sends the .war file to the Puppet master server which will then be used to provision the agent nodes.\r\n\r\n<img class=\"alignnone\" src=\"http://i.imgur.com/GZhTSYA.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"2058\" height=\"502\" />\r\n\r\nThis is not quite as elegant a solution as originally envisioned, but is necessary considering the limitations faced with the fact that we are not able to use CodeDeploy. The main issue with this setup is the increased overhead which is incurred and the unavoidable delay in updating agent nodes; while with CodeDeploy instances would begin to be updated immediately, with Puppet these updates will only apply when the agents check in to the master. By default this is every 30 minutes, but reducing this window will mean shorter turn-around times for updates at the cost of increased overhead. Nonetheless, we have successfully configured the backbones of a Continuous Delivery pipeline, and now must just finish up the Puppet configurations and then move on to other tasks.\r\n\r\nAlastair Kerr &amp; Bilal Hussain','Continuous Deployment Continued: CodeDeploy problem and workaround','','publish','open','open','','28','','','2015-08-20 08:45:16','2015-08-20 08:45:16','',0,'http://52.19.82.119/?p=28',0,'post','',0),(29,9,'2015-08-19 14:54:56','2015-08-19 14:54:56','Our initial plan was to use CodeDeploy, but after setting up the roles and profiles in AWS we found out that the Amazon accounts we had been provided with did not have access to the service. This was a big problem for us as CodeDeploy was a huge part of the Continuous Deployment pipeline and using it would have meant successful builds would swiftly and automatically be rolled out across our instances.\r\n\r\n<img class=\"alignnone\" src=\"http://i.imgur.com/Gn09XmN.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"582\" height=\"202\" />\r\n\r\nWithout this tool at our disposal we needed to find an alternative way. At this point we had fully implemented Continuous Integration with Jenkins for the Tomcat application, and so needed to work out how to get this build sent to our servers. We installed several Jenkins plugins to handle the post build steps; PostBuildScript allows for bash scripts to be executed as a post build action, and Artifact deployer allows for archived artifacts to be relocated to a more manageable location.\r\n\r\n<img class=\"alignnone\" src=\"http://i.imgur.com/fuUegLg.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"1844\" height=\"1156\" />\r\n\r\nThe specific implementation copies the archived build artifact (in the case of this Tomcat application, .war file) to a folder /builds/ owned by the Jenkins user, and then executes a simple scp transfer of the artifact to the Puppet master server (this involved configuring a limited permissions Jenkin user on the Puppet server with the public key from the Jenkins machine pasted into the authorized_keys for this new user). This meant that the Jenkins portion of the pipeline for this application was complete, with a push to the GitHub repository initiating a Jenkins build which, if successful, automatically sends the .war file to the Puppet master server which will then be used to provision the agent nodes.\r\n\r\n<img class=\"alignnone\" src=\"http://i.imgur.com/GZhTSYA.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"2058\" height=\"502\" />\r\n\r\nThis is not quite as elegant a solution as originally envisioned, but is necessary considering the limitations faced with the fact that we are not able to use CodeDeploy. The main issue with this setup is the increased overhead which is incurred and the unavoidable delay in updating agent nodes; while with CodeDeploy instances would begin to be updated immediately, with Puppet these updates will only apply when the agents check in to the master. By default this is every 30 minutes, but reducing this window will mean shorter turn-around times for updates at the cost of increased overhead. Nonetheless, we have successfully configured the backbones of a Continuous Deployment pipeline, and now must just finish up the Puppet configurations and then move on to other tasks.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;','','','inherit','open','open','','28-revision-v1','','','2015-08-19 14:54:56','2015-08-19 14:54:56','',28,'http://52.19.82.119/index.php/2015/08/19/28-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(30,9,'2015-08-19 14:59:42','2015-08-19 14:59:42','Our initial plan was to use CodeDeploy, but after setting up the roles and profiles in AWS we found out that the Amazon accounts we had been provided with did not have access to the service. This was a big problem for us as CodeDeploy was a huge part of the Continuous Deployment pipeline and using it would have meant successful builds would swiftly and automatically be rolled out across our instances.\n\n<img class=\"alignnone\" src=\"http://i.imgur.com/Gn09XmN.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"582\" height=\"202\" />\n\nWithout this tool at our disposal we needed to find an alternative way. At this point we had fully implemented Continuous Integration with Jenkins for the Tomcat application, and so needed to work out how to get this build sent to our servers. We installed several Jenkins plugins to handle the post build steps; PostBuildScript allows for bash scripts to be executed as a post build action, and Artifact deployer allows for archived artifacts to be relocated to a more manageable location.\n\n<img class=\"alignnone\" src=\"http://i.imgur.com/fuUegLg.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"1844\" height=\"1156\" />\n\nThe specific implementation copies the archived build artifact (in the case of this Tomcat application, .war file) to a folder /builds/ owned by the Jenkins user, and then executes a simple scp transfer of the artifact to the Puppet master server (this involved configuring a limited permissions Jenkin user on the Puppet server with the public key from the Jenkins machine pasted into the authorized_keys for this new user). This meant that the Jenkins portion of the pipeline for this application was complete, with a push to the GitHub repository initiating a Jenkins build which, if successful, automatically sends the .war file to the Puppet master server which will then be used to provision the agent nodes.\n\n<img class=\"alignnone\" src=\"http://i.imgur.com/GZhTSYA.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"2058\" height=\"502\" />\n\nThis is not quite as elegant a solution as originally envisioned, but is necessary considering the limitations faced with the fact that we are not able to use CodeDeploy. The main issue with this setup is the increased overhead which is incurred and the unavoidable delay in updating agent nodes; while with CodeDeploy instances would begin to be updated immediately, with Puppet these updates will only apply when the agents check in to the master. By default this is every 30 minutes, but reducing this window will mean shorter turn-around times for updates at the cost of increased overhead. Nonetheless, we have successfully configured the backbones of a Continuous Deployment pipeline, and now must just finish up the Puppet configurations and then move on to other tasks.\n\n&nbsp;','Continuous Deployment Continued: CodeDeploy','','inherit','open','open','','28-autosave-v1','','','2015-08-19 14:59:42','2015-08-19 14:59:42','',28,'http://52.19.82.119/index.php/2015/08/19/28-autosave-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(31,9,'2015-08-19 15:00:02','2015-08-19 15:00:02','Our initial plan was to use CodeDeploy, but after setting up the roles and profiles in AWS we found out that the Amazon accounts we had been provided with did not have access to the service. This was a big problem for us as CodeDeploy was a huge part of the Continuous Deployment pipeline and using it would have meant successful builds would swiftly and automatically be rolled out across our instances.\r\n\r\n<img class=\"alignnone\" src=\"http://i.imgur.com/Gn09XmN.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"582\" height=\"202\" />\r\n\r\nWithout this tool at our disposal we needed to find an alternative way. At this point we had fully implemented Continuous Integration with Jenkins for the Tomcat application, and so needed to work out how to get this build sent to our servers. We installed several Jenkins plugins to handle the post build steps; PostBuildScript allows for bash scripts to be executed as a post build action, and Artifact deployer allows for archived artifacts to be relocated to a more manageable location.\r\n\r\n<img class=\"alignnone\" src=\"http://i.imgur.com/fuUegLg.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"1844\" height=\"1156\" />\r\n\r\nThe specific implementation copies the archived build artifact (in the case of this Tomcat application, .war file) to a folder /builds/ owned by the Jenkins user, and then executes a simple scp transfer of the artifact to the Puppet master server (this involved configuring a limited permissions Jenkin user on the Puppet server with the public key from the Jenkins machine pasted into the authorized_keys for this new user). This meant that the Jenkins portion of the pipeline for this application was complete, with a push to the GitHub repository initiating a Jenkins build which, if successful, automatically sends the .war file to the Puppet master server which will then be used to provision the agent nodes.\r\n\r\n<img class=\"alignnone\" src=\"http://i.imgur.com/GZhTSYA.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"2058\" height=\"502\" />\r\n\r\nThis is not quite as elegant a solution as originally envisioned, but is necessary considering the limitations faced with the fact that we are not able to use CodeDeploy. The main issue with this setup is the increased overhead which is incurred and the unavoidable delay in updating agent nodes; while with CodeDeploy instances would begin to be updated immediately, with Puppet these updates will only apply when the agents check in to the master. By default this is every 30 minutes, but reducing this window will mean shorter turn-around times for updates at the cost of increased overhead. Nonetheless, we have successfully configured the backbones of a Continuous Deployment pipeline, and now must just finish up the Puppet configurations and then move on to other tasks.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;','Continuous Deployment Continued: CodeDeploy problem and workaround','','inherit','open','open','','28-revision-v1','','','2015-08-19 15:00:02','2015-08-19 15:00:02','',28,'http://52.19.82.119/index.php/2015/08/19/28-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(32,9,'2015-08-19 15:00:47','2015-08-19 15:00:47','Our initial plan was to use CodeDeploy, but after setting up the roles and profiles in AWS we found out that the Amazon accounts we had been provided with did not have access to the service. This was a big problem for us as CodeDeploy was a huge part of the Continuous Deployment pipeline and using it would have meant successful builds would swiftly and automatically be rolled out across our instances.\r\n\r\n<img class=\"alignnone\" src=\"http://i.imgur.com/Gn09XmN.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"582\" height=\"202\" />\r\n\r\nWithout this tool at our disposal we needed to find an alternative way. At this point we had fully implemented Continuous Integration with Jenkins for the Tomcat application, and so needed to work out how to get this build sent to our servers. We installed several Jenkins plugins to handle the post build steps; PostBuildScript allows for bash scripts to be executed as a post build action, and Artifact deployer allows for archived artifacts to be relocated to a more manageable location.\r\n\r\n<img class=\"alignnone\" src=\"http://i.imgur.com/fuUegLg.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"1844\" height=\"1156\" />\r\n\r\nThe specific implementation copies the archived build artifact (in the case of this Tomcat application, .war file) to a folder /builds/ owned by the Jenkins user, and then executes a simple scp transfer of the artifact to the Puppet master server (this involved configuring a limited permissions Jenkin user on the Puppet server with the public key from the Jenkins machine pasted into the authorized_keys for this new user). This meant that the Jenkins portion of the pipeline for this application was complete, with a push to the GitHub repository initiating a Jenkins build which, if successful, automatically sends the .war file to the Puppet master server which will then be used to provision the agent nodes.\r\n\r\n<img class=\"alignnone\" src=\"http://i.imgur.com/GZhTSYA.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"2058\" height=\"502\" />\r\n\r\nThis is not quite as elegant a solution as originally envisioned, but is necessary considering the limitations faced with the fact that we are not able to use CodeDeploy. The main issue with this setup is the increased overhead which is incurred and the unavoidable delay in updating agent nodes; while with CodeDeploy instances would begin to be updated immediately, with Puppet these updates will only apply when the agents check in to the master. By default this is every 30 minutes, but reducing this window will mean shorter turn-around times for updates at the cost of increased overhead. Nonetheless, we have successfully configured the backbones of a Continuous Deployment pipeline, and now must just finish up the Puppet configurations and then move on to other tasks.\r\n\r\nAlastair Kerr &amp; Bilal Hussain','Continuous Deployment Continued: CodeDeploy problem and workaround','','inherit','open','open','','28-revision-v1','','','2015-08-19 15:00:47','2015-08-19 15:00:47','',28,'http://52.19.82.119/index.php/2015/08/19/28-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(33,9,'2015-08-19 17:05:13','2015-08-19 17:05:13','While the Tomcat application has built in unit tests which are useful for allowing for a step of testing in the Continuous Integration environment (Jenkins), this cannot be said for the other web application. Unit Tests allow for builds to be verified before they are deployed, and this meant that we could have a fully automated Continuous Delivery pipeline without having to worry about faulty or broken builds being deployed to production servers. Without such a possibility for the 2nd application, we need a way for the developer(s) to test out their work in an environment mimicking the production environment so that they do not have to wait until their code is deployed live to find out if it will work.\r\n\r\n<img class=\"alignnone\" src=\"http://i.imgur.com/1P0thhr.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"1386\" height=\"754\" />\r\nThis comes in extension to whatever local testing they would do (e.g. in their IDE). Rather than spinning up a new online instance unnecessarily, the production environment can be replicated locally using a Virtual Machine (VM). However, a developer (presumably) would not want to spend lots of time configuring a server and installing all the packages they need, setting up the infrastructure etc. They want to spin something up that they can quickly and easily test their code on. For this reason, we decided it was a good idea to use Vagrant and Puppet to start up a Virtual Machine and bootstrap it with the necessary packages.\r\n\r\n<img class=\"alignnone\" src=\"http://i.imgur.com/x5r06TD.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"1182\" height=\"592\" />\r\n\r\nVagrant looks for and – if necessary – downloads the Ubuntu 14.04 vmbox from the internet at a given URL, and installs it before calling a bash script I wrote to install puppet. Vagrant is also configured to point to a ‘puppet’ folder with the manifests and modules (I used a LAMP stack module from puppetforge), which means that as soon as the process is finished the VM is setup with Apache2, MySQL and PHP. Furthermore, Vagrant was set up to configure a shared folder which the developer can place their website files in so that again, as soon as the VM is ready, their website/ web application is available rooted through to the host machine on localhost:8084.\r\n\r\n<img class=\"alignnone\" src=\"http://i.imgur.com/rwP9RZV.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"2248\" height=\"948\" />\r\n\r\nAlastair Kerr','Vagrant LAMP stack on Ubuntu 14.04 - Development/ Testing environment','','publish','open','open','','vagrant-lamp-stack-on-ubuntu-14-04-development-testing-environment','','','2015-08-20 08:44:52','2015-08-20 08:44:52','',0,'http://52.19.82.119/?p=33',0,'post','',0),(34,2,'2015-08-19 16:58:57','2015-08-19 16:58:57','<p style=\"text-align: left;\">To install code deploy, I first need to set up IAM roles and attach modified policies. The new roles are :</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li style=\"text-align: left;\">CodeDeploy</li>\r\n	<li style=\"text-align: left;\">EC2CodeDeploy</li>\r\n</ul>\r\nCode Deploy Policy:\r\n<pre>{\r\n\r\n \"Version\": \"2012-10-17\",\r\n\r\n \"Statement\": [\r\n\r\n   {\r\n\r\n     \"Action\": [\r\n\r\n       \"autoscaling:PutLifecycleHook\",\r\n\r\n       \"autoscaling:DeleteLifecycleHook\",\r\n\r\n       \"autoscaling:RecordLifecycleActionHeartbeat\",\r\n\r\n       \"autoscaling:CompleteLifecycleAction\",\r\n\r\n       \"autoscaling:DescribeAutoscalingGroups\",\r\n\r\n       \"autoscaling:PutInstanceInStandby\",\r\n\r\n       \"autoscaling:PutInstanceInService\",\r\n\r\n       \"ec2:Describe*\"\r\n\r\n     ],\r\n\r\n     \"Effect\": \"Allow\",\r\n\r\n     \"Resource\": \"*\"\r\n\r\n   }\r\n\r\n ]\r\n\r\n}\r\n\r\nOnce created, I need to edit the relationship trust by click edit relationship trust and replace the contents with the following:</pre>\r\n<pre>{\r\n\r\n \"Version\": \"2012-10-17\",\r\n\r\n \"Statement\": [\r\n\r\n   {\r\n\r\n     \"Sid\": \"\",\r\n\r\n     \"Effect\": \"Allow\",\r\n\r\n     \"Principal\": {\r\n\r\n       \"Service\": [\r\n\r\n         \"codedeploy.us-west-2.amazonaws.com\",\r\n\r\n         \"codedeploy.us-east-1.amazonaws.com\"\r\n\r\n       ]\r\n\r\n     },\r\n\r\n     \"Action\": \"sts:AssumeRole\"\r\n\r\n   }\r\n\r\n ]\r\n\r\n}\r\n\r\n\r\n</pre>\r\nRepeat the above step with EC2CodeDeploy but no need to update the trust policy. Once roles are created, launch an EC2 instance with the EC2DeployPolicy attached. In the EC2 instance, first install AWS command line. To install aws cli:\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li>Make sure python is installed by typing \"python --version\"</li>\r\n	<li>Sudo apt-get update</li>\r\n	<li>sudo apt-get install awscli</li>\r\n	<li>run aws help to check if it has installed successfully</li>\r\n</ol>\r\nThe following steps to install CodeDeploy Agent\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li>aws s3 cp s3://aws-codedeploy-eu-west-1/latest/install . --region eu-west1-1</li>\r\n	<li>chmod +x install</li>\r\n	<li>sed -i \"s/sleep(.*)/sleep(10)/\" install</li>\r\n	<li>Make sure ruby v2.0 is installed if not, run sudo apt-get install ruby2.0</li>\r\n	<li>./install auto</li>\r\n	<li>service codedeploy-agent status</li>\r\n</ol>\r\nWe ended up not using it as we did not have proper right to use code deploy service.','CodeDeploy (Documentation of progress)','','inherit','open','open','','24-revision-v1','','','2015-08-19 16:58:57','2015-08-19 16:58:57','',24,'http://52.19.82.119/index.php/2015/08/19/24-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(35,2,'2015-08-20 13:51:15','2015-08-20 13:51:15','We as a team decided to use AWS RDS MYSQL service as it is simple and integrated with Amazon Web Services. AWS allows the option to spread the databases through multiple sites by using the concept of master and slaves. The master copy is the main database instance and the slaves are replicating the database. Hence if the main database goes down, the slave takes over until the master is brought back up again.\r\n\r\nTo create RDS, we have to select RDS service the AWS Dashboard:\r\n\r\n<img class=\"alignnone\" src=\"http://i.imgur.com/i3D034w.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"838\" height=\"514\" />\r\n\r\nClick on Launch DB Instance to create a new instance\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<img class=\"alignnone\" src=\"http://i.imgur.com/yNuwEF8.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"1354\" height=\"494\" />\r\n\r\nThis will prompt the user to select an option to what type of Relation Database System the user would like to select. For this case, I selected MySQL as the developer\'s application requirement was built upon MySQL platform. Once it is selected, the user is prompted with whether to use the Multi AZ deployment service or to be used on one location. I selected MultiAZ deployment as this ensures my database is secure so for instance if my master database located in Ireland data centre site A goes down, the database is replicated to another Site e.g. Site B which will pick up the jobs until the Site A database comes back up.\r\n\r\nOnce that is complete, final step is to configure the instance specifications and settings. This includes, attaching a pre-configured policy, Database Instance Identifier, Master username and password. The next option takes the configurations further to network, security, backups and Database options which includes giving it a name. Most of it is by default pre-configured unless in some circumstances it needs to be changed.\r\n\r\nFinally once the instance is completed, the new instance starts to create itself and appears on the RDS dashboard.\r\n\r\n<img class=\"alignnone\" src=\"http://i.imgur.com/op92mJX.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"1936\" height=\"344\" />\r\n\r\n<strong>MYSQL Monitor</strong>\r\n\r\nTo integrate with the database, I need to have an instance where I can run MySQL utilities which can then be used to connect to the RDS database on amazon using the endpoint. The endpoint is a URL which runs over https and can be found in the Database information:\r\n\r\n<img class=\"alignnone\" src=\"http://i.imgur.com/jPyvXJu.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"1812\" height=\"720\" />\r\n\r\nOnce the endpoint is noted, I launched a new EC2 instance which was used to install mysql locally. Once it was installed, I ran the following command to access mysql:\r\n<blockquote>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\">mysql -u admin -P 3306 -h skydevop2015database.czk330ifgg3j.eu-west-1.rds.amazonaws.com -p**************</p>\r\n</blockquote>\r\nonce in mysql monitor, a script which was provided to us by the developer was executed to create the table and add the datasets into the table. Once the table was inserted, it was time to test it on the php app to ensure that the application is able to select datasets dynamically.\r\n\r\nTo test it, I created a new test EC2 instance which was used to the deploy the application running on LAMP stack except the MYSQL was not really needed as we have a RDS instance running in Amazon Cloud. The only thing that needed modifying was defining the php file to integrate with RDS instance. To do this, I had to change the file useful.php:\r\n\r\n<img class=\"alignnone\" src=\"http://i.imgur.com/IsnYyAB.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"1810\" height=\"258\" />\r\n\r\nOnce this was complete, the webapp was successfully able to access the data from the users table so they could be used to log in.','RDS AWS MYSQL','','publish','open','open','','rds-aws-mysql','','','2015-08-20 14:17:03','2015-08-20 14:17:03','',0,'http://52.19.82.119/?p=35',0,'post','',0),(36,2,'2015-08-19 16:59:17','2015-08-19 16:59:17','','RDS AWS MYSQL','','inherit','open','open','','35-revision-v1','','','2015-08-19 16:59:17','2015-08-19 16:59:17','',35,'http://52.19.82.119/index.php/2015/08/19/35-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(37,9,'2015-08-19 17:05:13','2015-08-19 17:05:13','While the Tomcat application has built in unit tests which are useful for allowing for a step of testing in the Continuous Integration environment (Jenkins), this cannot be said for the other web application. Unit Tests allow for builds to be verified before they are deployed, and this meant that we could have a fully automated Continuous Deployment pipeline without having to worry about faulty or broken builds being deployed to production servers. Without such a possibility for the 2nd application, we need a way for the developer(s) to test out their work in an environment mimicking the production environment so that they do not have to wait until their code is deployed live to find out if it will work.\r\n\r\n<img class=\"alignnone\" src=\"http://i.imgur.com/1P0thhr.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"1386\" height=\"754\" />\r\nThis comes in extension to whatever local testing they would do (e.g. in their IDE). Rather than spinning up a new online instance unnecessarily, the production environment can be replicated locally using a Virtual Machine (VM). However, a developer (presumably) would not want to spend lots of time configuring a server and installing all the packages they need, setting up the infrastructure etc. They want to spin something up that they can quickly and easily test their code on. For this reason, we decided it was a good idea to use Vagrant and Puppet to start up a Virtual Machine and bootstrap it with the necessary packages.\r\n\r\n<img class=\"alignnone\" src=\"http://i.imgur.com/x5r06TD.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"1182\" height=\"592\" />\r\n\r\nVagrant looks for and – if necessary – downloads the Ubuntu 14.04 vmbox from the internet at a given URL, and installs it before calling a bash script I wrote to install puppet. Vagrant is also configured to point to a ‘puppet’ folder with the manifests and modules (I used a LAMP stack module from puppetforge), which means that as soon as the process is finished the VM is setup with Apache2, MySQL and PHP. Furthermore, Vagrant was set up to configure a shared folder which the developer can place their website files in so that again, as soon as the VM is ready, their website/ web application is available rooted through to the host machine on localhost:8084.\r\n\r\n<img class=\"alignnone\" src=\"http://i.imgur.com/rwP9RZV.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"2248\" height=\"948\" />\r\n\r\nAlastair Kerr','Vagrant LAMP stack on Ubuntu 14.04 - Development/ Testing environment','','inherit','open','open','','33-revision-v1','','','2015-08-19 17:05:13','2015-08-19 17:05:13','',33,'http://52.19.82.119/index.php/2015/08/19/33-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(38,2,'2015-08-19 17:11:34','2015-08-19 17:11:34','We as a team decided to use AWS RDS MYSQL service as it is simple and integrated with Amazon Web Services. AWS allows the option to spread the databases through multiple sites by using the concept of master and slaves. The master copy is the main database instance and the slaves are replicating the database. Hence if the main database goes down, the slave takes over until the master is brought back up again.\r\n\r\nTo create RDS, we have to select RDS service the AWS Dashboard:\r\n\r\n<img class=\"alignnone\" src=\"http://i.imgur.com/i3D034w.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"838\" height=\"514\" />\r\n\r\nClick on Launch DB Instance to create a new instance\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<img class=\"alignnone\" src=\"http://i.imgur.com/yNuwEF8.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"1354\" height=\"494\" />','RDS AWS MYSQL','','inherit','open','open','','35-revision-v1','','','2015-08-19 17:11:34','2015-08-19 17:11:34','',35,'http://52.19.82.119/index.php/2015/08/19/35-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(39,5,'2015-08-19 20:27:11','2015-08-19 20:27:11','To make the sky.pem usable I changed the permissions:\r\n\r\n<strong><em>$ chmod 600 sky.pem</em></strong>\r\n\r\nTo start the installing puppet master I logged into the puppet server via SSH:\r\n\r\n<img class=\"alignnone\" src=\"http://i.imgur.com/fkePs9y.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"692\" height=\"494\" />\r\n\r\nI then logged into the root user:\r\n\r\n<strong><em>ubuntu@ip-172-31-21-124:~$ sudo bash</em></strong>\r\n\r\nI then updated the hostname:\r\n\r\n<strong><em>root@ip-172-31-21-124:~# sudo hostname master</em></strong>\r\n\r\n<strong><em>root@ip-172-31-21-124:~# sudo su -c \'echo master &gt; /etc/hostname\'</em></strong>\r\n\r\n<strong><em>root@ip-172-31-21-124:~# sudo su -c \'echo 52.16.190.24 master master.acme.com &gt;&gt;/etc/hosts\'</em></strong>\r\n\r\nWe are now ready to install the puppet enterprise server.\r\n\r\nTo start I downloaded the source code:\r\n\r\n<strong><em>root@ip-172-31-21-124:~# </em>wget https://s3-eu-west-1.amazonaws.com/puppet-installers/puppet-enterprise-3.7.1-ubuntu-14.04-amd64.tar.tar</strong>\r\n\r\nunzip the source code:\r\n\r\n<strong><em>root@ip-172-31-21-124:~# tar -xvf puppet-enterprise-3.7.1-ubuntu-14.04-amd64.tar.tar</em></strong>\r\n\r\nRun the installer:\r\n\r\n<strong><em>root@ip-172-31-21-124:~# cd puppet-enterprise-3.7.1-ubuntu-14.04-amd64</em></strong>\r\n\r\n<strong><em>root@ip-172-31-21-124:~/puppet-enterprise-3.7.1-ubuntu-14.04-amd64# ./puppet-enterprise-installer</em></strong>\r\n\r\nOnce the installer was ready I navigated to my browser and continued the installation:\r\n\r\n<img class=\"alignnone\" src=\"http://i.imgur.com/JUax34C.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"692\" height=\"494\" />\r\n\r\nI had to accept the ssl certificate as it is self-signed:\r\n\r\n<img class=\"alignnone\" src=\"http://i.imgur.com/kUwB23F.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"692\" height=\"375\" />\r\n\r\nI then followed the installation guide to complete the installation process:\r\n\r\n<img class=\"alignnone\" src=\"http://i.imgur.com/228lJdf.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"692\" height=\"645\" /><img class=\"alignnone\" src=\"http://i.imgur.com/9Vooj02.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"692\" height=\"366\" /><img class=\"alignnone\" src=\"http://i.imgur.com/4tEAASE.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"692\" height=\"374\" />\r\n\r\n&nbsp;','Installing puppet enterprise','','publish','open','open','','installing-puppet-enterprise','','','2015-08-19 20:27:11','2015-08-19 20:27:11','',0,'http://52.19.82.119/?p=39',0,'post','',0),(40,5,'2015-08-19 20:27:11','2015-08-19 20:27:11','To make the sky.pem usable I changed the permissions:\r\n\r\n<strong><em>$ chmod 600 sky.pem</em></strong>\r\n\r\nTo start the installing puppet master I logged into the puppet server via SSH:\r\n\r\n<img class=\"alignnone\" src=\"http://i.imgur.com/fkePs9y.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"692\" height=\"494\" />\r\n\r\nI then logged into the root user:\r\n\r\n<strong><em>ubuntu@ip-172-31-21-124:~$ sudo bash</em></strong>\r\n\r\nI then updated the hostname:\r\n\r\n<strong><em>root@ip-172-31-21-124:~# sudo hostname master</em></strong>\r\n\r\n<strong><em>root@ip-172-31-21-124:~# sudo su -c \'echo master &gt; /etc/hostname\'</em></strong>\r\n\r\n<strong><em>root@ip-172-31-21-124:~# sudo su -c \'echo 52.16.190.24 master master.acme.com &gt;&gt;/etc/hosts\'</em></strong>\r\n\r\nWe are now ready to install the puppet enterprise server.\r\n\r\nTo start I downloaded the source code:\r\n\r\n<strong><em>root@ip-172-31-21-124:~# </em>wget https://s3-eu-west-1.amazonaws.com/puppet-installers/puppet-enterprise-3.7.1-ubuntu-14.04-amd64.tar.tar</strong>\r\n\r\nunzip the source code:\r\n\r\n<strong><em>root@ip-172-31-21-124:~# tar -xvf puppet-enterprise-3.7.1-ubuntu-14.04-amd64.tar.tar</em></strong>\r\n\r\nRun the installer:\r\n\r\n<strong><em>root@ip-172-31-21-124:~# cd puppet-enterprise-3.7.1-ubuntu-14.04-amd64</em></strong>\r\n\r\n<strong><em>root@ip-172-31-21-124:~/puppet-enterprise-3.7.1-ubuntu-14.04-amd64# ./puppet-enterprise-installer</em></strong>\r\n\r\nOnce the installer was ready I navigated to my browser and continued the installation:\r\n\r\n<img class=\"alignnone\" src=\"http://i.imgur.com/JUax34C.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"692\" height=\"494\" />\r\n\r\nI had to accept the ssl certificate as it is self-signed:\r\n\r\n<img class=\"alignnone\" src=\"http://i.imgur.com/kUwB23F.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"692\" height=\"375\" />\r\n\r\nI then followed the installation guide to complete the installation process:\r\n\r\n<img class=\"alignnone\" src=\"http://i.imgur.com/228lJdf.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"692\" height=\"645\" /><img class=\"alignnone\" src=\"http://i.imgur.com/9Vooj02.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"692\" height=\"366\" /><img class=\"alignnone\" src=\"http://i.imgur.com/4tEAASE.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"692\" height=\"374\" />\r\n\r\n&nbsp;','Installing puppet enterprise','','inherit','open','open','','39-revision-v1','','','2015-08-19 20:27:11','2015-08-19 20:27:11','',39,'http://52.19.82.119/index.php/2015/08/19/39-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(41,5,'2015-08-19 20:35:51','2015-08-19 20:35:51','First I selected the image for the puppet server. I selected Ubuntu 14.04 (64 bit) as this is the chosen Linux distribution for the case study.\r\n\r\n<img class=\"alignnone\" src=\"http://i.imgur.com/rmjL6HV.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"692\" height=\"280\" />\r\n\r\nI then selected the puppet master instance type. I chose to use a t2.large instance that had 2 CPU’s and 8GB of RAM.\r\n\r\n<img class=\"alignnone\" src=\"http://i.imgur.com/0WR46mp.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"692\" height=\"299\" />\r\n\r\nI then gave the puppet server 50GB of disc space:\r\n\r\n<img class=\"alignnone\" src=\"http://i.imgur.com/nJHo6yy.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"692\" height=\"252\" />\r\n\r\nI added a ‘name’ tag to the server of ‘puppet-master’ so that it can be easily identified via the AWS console:\r\n\r\n<img class=\"alignnone\" src=\"http://i.imgur.com/7xGha72.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"692\" height=\"146\" />\r\n\r\nIn order to access the puppet server I added the following ports to a new security group ‘puppet master’ and assigned this to the puppet master instance:\r\n\r\n<img class=\"alignnone\" src=\"http://i.imgur.com/Gg8bM9H.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"692\" height=\"275\" />\r\n\r\n8140\r\n\r\n3000\r\n\r\n22\r\n\r\n80\r\n\r\n443\r\n\r\n4433\r\n\r\n61613\r\n\r\n5432\r\n\r\n8081\r\n\r\n4435\r\n\r\nThe puppet master node is the first node being added to the amazon web service configuration. I added a new key pair called ‘sky’ which will be assigned to future servers in order to gain access them.\r\n\r\n<img class=\"alignnone\" src=\"http://i.imgur.com/vTYK4MJ.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"692\" height=\"323\" />\r\n\r\nThe AWS instance has now been created:\r\n\r\n<img class=\"alignnone\" src=\"http://i.imgur.com/FJ2SUSY.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"692\" height=\"199\" />','Adding a puppet master instance to AWS','','publish','open','open','','adding-a-puppet-master-instance-to-aws','','','2015-08-19 20:35:51','2015-08-19 20:35:51','',0,'http://52.19.82.119/?p=41',0,'post','',0),(42,5,'2015-08-19 20:35:51','2015-08-19 20:35:51','First I selected the image for the puppet server. I selected Ubuntu 14.04 (64 bit) as this is the chosen Linux distribution for the case study.\r\n\r\n<img class=\"alignnone\" src=\"http://i.imgur.com/rmjL6HV.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"692\" height=\"280\" />\r\n\r\nI then selected the puppet master instance type. I chose to use a t2.large instance that had 2 CPU’s and 8GB of RAM.\r\n\r\n<img class=\"alignnone\" src=\"http://i.imgur.com/0WR46mp.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"692\" height=\"299\" />\r\n\r\nI then gave the puppet server 50GB of disc space:\r\n\r\n<img class=\"alignnone\" src=\"http://i.imgur.com/nJHo6yy.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"692\" height=\"252\" />\r\n\r\nI added a ‘name’ tag to the server of ‘puppet-master’ so that it can be easily identified via the AWS console:\r\n\r\n<img class=\"alignnone\" src=\"http://i.imgur.com/7xGha72.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"692\" height=\"146\" />\r\n\r\nIn order to access the puppet server I added the following ports to a new security group ‘puppet master’ and assigned this to the puppet master instance:\r\n\r\n<img class=\"alignnone\" src=\"http://i.imgur.com/Gg8bM9H.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"692\" height=\"275\" />\r\n\r\n8140\r\n\r\n3000\r\n\r\n22\r\n\r\n80\r\n\r\n443\r\n\r\n4433\r\n\r\n61613\r\n\r\n5432\r\n\r\n8081\r\n\r\n4435\r\n\r\nThe puppet master node is the first node being added to the amazon web service configuration. I added a new key pair called ‘sky’ which will be assigned to future servers in order to gain access them.\r\n\r\n<img class=\"alignnone\" src=\"http://i.imgur.com/vTYK4MJ.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"692\" height=\"323\" />\r\n\r\nThe AWS instance has now been created:\r\n\r\n<img class=\"alignnone\" src=\"http://i.imgur.com/FJ2SUSY.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"692\" height=\"199\" />','Adding a puppet master instance to AWS','','inherit','open','open','','41-revision-v1','','','2015-08-19 20:35:51','2015-08-19 20:35:51','',41,'http://52.19.82.119/index.php/2015/08/19/41-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(43,5,'2015-08-19 21:02:22','2015-08-19 21:02:22','The Java web app needs to be deployed by puppet to ensure that continuous delivery can be achieved. Changes to the application will be pushed to the remote repo by the development team and from there Jenkins will take the code and build the application.\r\n\r\nIf the application build fails, an alert email will be sent and the process will stop, but if all tests are successful, the code will be passed onto puppet so that the changes can be introduced to the new system.\r\n\r\nOnce Jenkins has passed all tests it will use a bash script built by Ali and copy the tomcat.war file into the Jenkins user\'s directory within the puppet master node:\r\n\r\n<img class=\"alignnone\" src=\"http://i.imgur.com/W4vk72l.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"482\" height=\"410\" />\r\n\r\nTo allow the agent_tomcat module within puppet to access the war file I created a symbolic link between the Jenkins user directory, and the puppet module files (/etc/puppetlabs/puppet/modules/agent_tomcat/files).\r\n\r\n<strong>ln -s /etc/puppetlabs/puppet/modules/agent_tomcat/files/ /home/jenkins/war_files</strong>\r\n\r\nWhen building the puppet manifest for java web app agents I added code for:\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Installing Tomcat 7</li>\r\n	<li>Load in the modified configuration (changed to port 80)</li>\r\n	<li>Change Ubuntu settings via a bash script to allow Tomcat to run on a privileged port (port 1 - 1024)</li>\r\n	<li> Ensure webapps directory existed</li>\r\n	<li>Copy tomcat.war file to remote server</li>\r\n	<li>Modify index page of the ROOT website so that end users are redirected to the correct application.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\nclass agent_tomcat {\r\n\r\n# Install Tomcat\r\npackage {\'tomcat7\':\r\nensure =&gt; present,\r\n}\r\n\r\n# Load in config file\r\nfile {\'/etc/tomcat7/server.xml\':\r\nensure =&gt; file,\r\nowner =&gt; \'root\',\r\ngroup =&gt; \'tomcat7\',\r\nsource =&gt; \'puppet:///modules/agent_tomcat/server.xml\',\r\nrequire =&gt; Package[\'tomcat7\'],\r\n}\r\n\r\n# Update /etc/default/tomcat7 to ensure tomcat can run on priv port\r\nfile {\'/etc/default/tomcat7\':\r\nensure =&gt; file,\r\nowner =&gt; \'root\',\r\ngroup =&gt; \'root\',\r\nsource =&gt; \'puppet:///modules/agent_tomcat/tomcat7\',\r\nrequire =&gt; Package[\'tomcat7\'],\r\n}\r\n\r\nfile { \'my_bash_script\':\r\nensure =&gt; \'file\',\r\nsource =&gt; \'puppet:///modules/agent_tomcat/tomcat_ports.sh\',\r\npath =&gt; \'/usr/local/bin/tomcat_ports.sh\',\r\nowner =&gt; \'root\',\r\ngroup =&gt; \'root\',\r\nmode =&gt; \'0744\', # Use 0700 if it is sensitive\r\nnotify =&gt; Exec[\'run_my_script\'],\r\n}\r\n\r\nexec { \'run_my_script\':\r\ncommand =&gt; \'/usr/local/bin/tomcat_ports.sh\',\r\nrefreshonly =&gt; true,\r\n}\r\n\r\n# Copy web files over to root\r\nfile {\'/var/lib/tomcat7\':\r\nensure =&gt; directory,\r\n}\r\n\r\nfile {\'/var/lib/tomcat7/webapps\':\r\nensure =&gt; directory,\r\n}\r\n\r\nfile {\'/var/lib/tomcat7/webapps/tomcat.war\':\r\nensure =&gt; file,\r\nsource =&gt; \'puppet:///modules/agent_tomcat/tomcat.war\',\r\n}\r\n\r\n# Set up redirect for web app\r\nfile {\'/var/lib/tomcat7/webapps/ROOT/index.html\':\r\nensure =&gt; file,\r\nsource =&gt; \'puppet:///modules/agent_tomcat/index.html\',\r\n}\r\n\r\nservice {\'tomcat7\':\r\nensure =&gt; running,\r\n\r\n}\r\n}\r\n\r\nOnce the script had been created, I spun up a few aws instances to ensure that the puppet scripts installed all packages and provisioned the server correctly.\r\n\r\nTo identify nodes when they connect to puppet I created a new group and added a ec2_security_group parameter so that the nodes can be identified via their allocated security group:\r\n\r\n<img class=\"alignnone\" src=\"http://i.imgur.com/4kLgGdb.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"1248\" height=\"549\" />\r\n\r\n<img class=\"alignnone\" src=\"http://i.imgur.com/DiL7kBP.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"1250\" height=\"575\" />','Deploying the Java app via Puppet','','publish','open','open','','deploying-the-java-app-via-puppet','','','2015-08-19 21:02:22','2015-08-19 21:02:22','',0,'http://52.19.82.119/?p=43',0,'post','',0),(44,5,'2015-08-19 21:02:22','2015-08-19 21:02:22','The Java web app needs to be deployed by puppet to ensure that continuous delivery can be achieved. Changes to the application will be pushed to the remote repo by the development team and from there Jenkins will take the code and build the application.\r\n\r\nIf the application build fails, an alert email will be sent and the process will stop, but if all tests are successful, the code will be passed onto puppet so that the changes can be introduced to the new system.\r\n\r\nOnce Jenkins has passed all tests it will use a bash script built by Ali and copy the tomcat.war file into the Jenkins user\'s directory within the puppet master node:\r\n\r\n<img class=\"alignnone\" src=\"http://i.imgur.com/W4vk72l.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"482\" height=\"410\" />\r\n\r\nTo allow the agent_tomcat module within puppet to access the war file I created a symbolic link between the Jenkins user directory, and the puppet module files (/etc/puppetlabs/puppet/modules/agent_tomcat/files).\r\n\r\n<strong>ln -s /etc/puppetlabs/puppet/modules/agent_tomcat/files/ /home/jenkins/war_files</strong>\r\n\r\nWhen building the puppet manifest for java web app agents I added code for:\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Installing Tomcat 7</li>\r\n	<li>Load in the modified configuration (changed to port 80)</li>\r\n	<li>Change Ubuntu settings via a bash script to allow Tomcat to run on a privileged port (port 1 - 1024)</li>\r\n	<li> Ensure webapps directory existed</li>\r\n	<li>Copy tomcat.war file to remote server</li>\r\n	<li>Modify index page of the ROOT website so that end users are redirected to the correct application.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\nclass agent_tomcat {\r\n\r\n# Install Tomcat\r\npackage {\'tomcat7\':\r\nensure =&gt; present,\r\n}\r\n\r\n# Load in config file\r\nfile {\'/etc/tomcat7/server.xml\':\r\nensure =&gt; file,\r\nowner =&gt; \'root\',\r\ngroup =&gt; \'tomcat7\',\r\nsource =&gt; \'puppet:///modules/agent_tomcat/server.xml\',\r\nrequire =&gt; Package[\'tomcat7\'],\r\n}\r\n\r\n# Update /etc/default/tomcat7 to ensure tomcat can run on priv port\r\nfile {\'/etc/default/tomcat7\':\r\nensure =&gt; file,\r\nowner =&gt; \'root\',\r\ngroup =&gt; \'root\',\r\nsource =&gt; \'puppet:///modules/agent_tomcat/tomcat7\',\r\nrequire =&gt; Package[\'tomcat7\'],\r\n}\r\n\r\nfile { \'my_bash_script\':\r\nensure =&gt; \'file\',\r\nsource =&gt; \'puppet:///modules/agent_tomcat/tomcat_ports.sh\',\r\npath =&gt; \'/usr/local/bin/tomcat_ports.sh\',\r\nowner =&gt; \'root\',\r\ngroup =&gt; \'root\',\r\nmode =&gt; \'0744\', # Use 0700 if it is sensitive\r\nnotify =&gt; Exec[\'run_my_script\'],\r\n}\r\n\r\nexec { \'run_my_script\':\r\ncommand =&gt; \'/usr/local/bin/tomcat_ports.sh\',\r\nrefreshonly =&gt; true,\r\n}\r\n\r\n# Copy web files over to root\r\nfile {\'/var/lib/tomcat7\':\r\nensure =&gt; directory,\r\n}\r\n\r\nfile {\'/var/lib/tomcat7/webapps\':\r\nensure =&gt; directory,\r\n}\r\n\r\nfile {\'/var/lib/tomcat7/webapps/tomcat.war\':\r\nensure =&gt; file,\r\nsource =&gt; \'puppet:///modules/agent_tomcat/tomcat.war\',\r\n}\r\n\r\n# Set up redirect for web app\r\nfile {\'/var/lib/tomcat7/webapps/ROOT/index.html\':\r\nensure =&gt; file,\r\nsource =&gt; \'puppet:///modules/agent_tomcat/index.html\',\r\n}\r\n\r\nservice {\'tomcat7\':\r\nensure =&gt; running,\r\n\r\n}\r\n}\r\n\r\nOnce the script had been created, I spun up a few aws instances to ensure that the puppet scripts installed all packages and provisioned the server correctly.\r\n\r\nTo identify nodes when they connect to puppet I created a new group and added a ec2_security_group parameter so that the nodes can be identified via their allocated security group:\r\n\r\n<img class=\"alignnone\" src=\"http://i.imgur.com/4kLgGdb.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"1248\" height=\"549\" />\r\n\r\n<img class=\"alignnone\" src=\"http://i.imgur.com/DiL7kBP.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"1250\" height=\"575\" />','Deploying the Java app via Puppet','','inherit','open','open','','43-revision-v1','','','2015-08-19 21:02:22','2015-08-19 21:02:22','',43,'http://52.19.82.119/index.php/2015/08/19/43-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(45,9,'2015-08-20 08:38:56','2015-08-20 08:38:56','<strong>Scott</strong>\r\n\r\nYesterday Scott provisioned Tomcat agents with puppet and worked on linking with the Puppet master to complete the Continuous Delivery pipeline. He set up configrations and a symlink so that the Puppet master could integrate the application’s war file into the build.\r\n\r\nToday he will build a LAMP stack with puppet (minus MySQL as we will be using AWS RDS) for the agent nodes , and set up autoscaling / load balancer with James.\r\n\r\nBlockages: licensing issue for puppet, only 10 licenses for puppet enterprise. Have to manually revoke licenses for destroyed servers if we want to issue more<strong>\r\n</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Michael</strong>\r\n\r\nToday Michael will be setting up AWS CloudWatch for monitoring of the servers, and generally getting up to speed with the project<strong>\r\n</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>James</strong>\r\n\r\nYesterday James worked on the load balancer and autoscaling groups in AWS and got it working.\r\n\r\nToday he will be applying this to the final setup so that we have a more robust infrastructure.<strong>\r\n</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Bilal</strong>\r\n\r\nYesterday Bilal and Ali finished setting up Jenkins. Bilal worked on CodeDeploy but unfortunately found that we wouldn’t be able to use it. He also set up RDS with redundancy and tested this with the 2<sup>nd</sup> webapp.\r\n\r\nToday he will work on backup scripts for the SQL database and store these on S3 bucket.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Ali</strong>\r\n\r\nYesterday Ali and Bilal set up Jenkin’s final configurations for the Continuous Delivery pipeline, adding post build actions to send build artifacts to the puppet master for deployment. Ali also set up Vagrant to create a virtual environment with LAMP stack that developers can use to develop or test out code.\r\n\r\nToday he will make sure everything in Jenkins is configured properly, and take advantage of slack to see where else he can help out.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>John</strong>\r\n\r\nToday I will assisting Michael with CloudWatch which we will use to monitor the servers. I will also be updating myself on yesterdays tasks in preparation for Friday due to my absence.','Standup Meeting 20th August 2015','','publish','open','open','','standup-meeting-20th-august-2015','','','2015-08-20 09:07:17','2015-08-20 09:07:17','',0,'http://52.19.82.119/?p=45',0,'post','',0),(46,9,'2015-08-20 08:38:56','2015-08-20 08:38:56','<strong>Scott</strong>\r\n\r\nYesterday Scott provisioned Tomcat agents with puppet and worked on linking with the Puppet master to complete the Continuous Deployment pipeline. He set up configrations and a symlink so that the Puppet master could integrate the application’s war file into the build.\r\n\r\nToday he will build a LAMP stack with puppet (minus MySQL as we will be using AWS RDS) for the agent nodes , and set up autoscaling / load balancer with James.\r\n\r\nBlockages: licensing issue for puppet, only 10 licenses for puppet enterprise. Have to manually revoke licenses for destroyed servers if we want to issue more<strong>\r\n</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Michael</strong>\r\n\r\nToday Michael will be setting up AWS CloudWatch for monitoring of the servers, and generally getting up to speed with the project<strong>\r\n</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>James</strong>\r\n\r\nYesterday James worked on the load balancer and autoscaling groups in AWS and got it working.\r\n\r\nToday he will be applying this to the final setup so that we have a more robust infrastructure.<strong>\r\n</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Bilal</strong>\r\n\r\nYesterday Bilal and Ali finished setting up Jenkins. Bilal worked on CodeDeploy but unfortunately found that we wouldn’t be able to use it. He also set up RDS with redundancy and tested this with the 2<sup>nd</sup> webapp.\r\n\r\nToday he will work on backup scripts for the SQL database and store these on S3 bucket.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Ali</strong>\r\n\r\nYesterday Ali and Bilal set up Jenkin’s final configurations for the Continuous Deployment pipeline, adding post build actions to send build artifacts to the puppet master for deployment. Ali also set up Vagrant to create a virtual environment with LAMP stack that developers can use to develop or test out code.\r\n\r\nToday he will make sure everything in Jenkins is configured properly, and take advantage of slack to see where else he can help out.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>John</strong>\r\n\r\nTBD','Standup Meeting 20th August 2015','','inherit','open','open','','45-revision-v1','','','2015-08-20 08:38:56','2015-08-20 08:38:56','',45,'http://52.19.82.119/index.php/2015/08/20/45-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(47,9,'2015-08-20 08:43:55','2015-08-20 08:43:55','A core part of our overall system design is the Continuous Delivery pipeline, the primary software tools used being Jenkins and Amazon Web Services CodeDeploy. The overall aim of implementing these technologies was to allow for Continuous Deployment through linking remote GitHub repositories to a Jenkins server which builds the code, tests it, and – assuming these tests pass – instigates CodeDeploy to deploy the new build across the relevant AWS instances.\r\n\r\n<img class=\"alignnone\" src=\"http://i.imgur.com/ZInjSkH.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"2550\" height=\"1372\" />\r\n\r\nBilal and myself were responsible for this section of the project, and the first step in this process was to manually configure Jenkins. This helped us get a better understanding of how the software worked, and laid the foundations for a largely automated process later. Ubuntu 14.04 was the platform for this server, and setting up the CI platform necessitated installing Jenkins, git plugins, JDK7, maven and also apache2 (not necessary, but useful for enabling us to proxy Jenkins through to port 80 and using the public DNS, making the Jenkins interface accessible through the world wide web with a domain name assigned by Amazon). Lots of configurations needed to be made through the Jenkins interface, for example configuring the <em>MAVEN HOME</em> location so that the developer’s Java app could be built with Jenkins. Importantly, considering the globally accessible nature of this server, security configurations were made so that anonymous users have read only access and an administrator login allows for full privileges.\r\n\r\nA crucial requirement for facilitating this build was to link the relevant GitHub repository to the Jenkins server. Firstly, an SSH key was generated for the ‘jenkins’ user on the Jenkins server, which was used as a Deploy Key for the specific repository, a measure that was implemented through the settings in GitHub. This authentication was confirmed through the command line on the Jenkins server, as shown below.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>jenkins@ip-172-31-37-36:/usr/share/maven$ ssh-keygen</em>\r\n<em>Generating public/private rsa key pair.</em>\r\n<em>Enter file in which to save the key (/var/lib/jenkins/.ssh/id_rsa):</em>\r\n<em>Created directory \'/var/lib/jenkins/.ssh\'.</em>\r\n<em>Enter passphrase (empty for no passphrase):</em>\r\n<em>Enter same passphrase again:</em>\r\n<em>Your identification has been saved in /var/lib/jenkins/.ssh/id_rsa.</em>\r\n<em>Your public key has been saved in /var/lib/jenkins/.ssh/id_rsa.pub.</em>\r\n<em>The key fingerprint is:</em>\r\n<em>de:08:ce:0a:ee:a7:d4:d6:29:68:70:29:ee:14:6a:a9 jenkins@ip-172-31-37-36</em>\r\n<em>The key\'s randomart image is:</em>\r\n<em>+--[ RSA 2048]----+</em>\r\n<em>|                            |</em>\r\n<em>|                            |</em>\r\n<em>|                            |</em>\r\n<em>|    .                       |</em>\r\n<em>|o.o     .  S             |</em>\r\n<em>|o+oo + + o          |</em>\r\n<em>|.== + = o .            |</em>\r\n<em>|=+ o.o                  |</em>\r\n<em>|Eo+o.                   |</em>\r\n<em>+-----------------------+</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>jenkins@ip-172-31-37-36:/usr/share/maven$ ssh git@github.com</em>\r\n<em>PTY allocation request failed on channel 0</em>\r\n<em>Hi AKerr94/jenkins-test! You\'ve successfully authenticated, but GitHub does not provide shell access.</em>\r\n<em>Connection to github.com closed.</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nWith the Deploy Key successfully associated, the next measure we took was to setup a webhook. This means that an action on GitHub (such as a push to the repository) triggers an action, sending this information to the Jenkins server so that it can act appropriately (in our case we did indeed want Jenkins to automatically trigger a build following a push to the linked repository). This had to be setup in the repository’s settings with special links that Jenkins could handle, and on the Jenkins side the GitHub repository had to be linked along with authorization tokens for the associated account. Linking Jenkins and GitHub like this is a little more complex than other methods but doing so in this way means that Jenkins can build from a private repository, which is beneficial for example if developers do not want their code to be made public. Successful builds will need to trigger AWS CodeDeploy to deploy the application across our instances, and failed builds are logged, with monitoring available through the Jenkins interface and dashboards giving an overview of build health and allowing for an audit trail that can be used for error troubleshooting.\r\n\r\n<img class=\"alignnone\" src=\"http://i.imgur.com/DKPyFwU.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"2548\" height=\"1170\" />\r\n\r\nIn the case of a build failure Jenkins can also be configured to notify administrators or specific email accounts (such as the developer whose build is broken!). We tested this functionality with an email address for our team.\r\n\r\n<img class=\"alignnone\" src=\"http://i.imgur.com/JYhKt2X.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"1718\" height=\"590\" />\r\n\r\nWith the Continuous Integration portion of the setup working, we then worked on automating the process. After initial issues with Puppet configurations, and, considering that we were already using the advanced options of AWS to provision Jenkins on our initial test servers with bash scripts, we decided to extend these with a more involved and all-round script that provisioned a Jenkins server pre-configured with many of the necessary plugins and setup options, for example dynamically inputting the initiated instances public DNS into the Apache configuration in order to allow for access over the web through the Amazon hostname (otherwise this would simply lead to the Apache default splashpage on port 80 rather than redirecting to the Jenkins interface).\r\n\r\n<img class=\"alignnone\" src=\"http://i.imgur.com/Yce5rxu.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"1532\" height=\"1010\" />\r\n\r\nWith this bash script a Jenkins server can be provisioned extremely quickly with AWS, and serves as a possible route for backup/ disaster recovery in the event of a server failure, although our main disaster recovery mechanism for the Jenkins server comes in the form of an AMI created from this final server configuration, which can be deployed as an AWS instance as needed. Therefore, this AMI would be our first port of call in the event of server failure, but with the bash script we have redundancy, so, for example, were AWS to fail, or, should we want to switch to a different service, we would not be reliant on these services and could provision another server with another provider.\r\n\r\nThe next steps we will take will be to setup CodeDeploy and connect this to Jenkins, so that successful builds will be automatically deployed across our infrastructure. In this manner, we will have achieved Continuous Deployment as pushes to the GitHub repository will initiate Jenkins builds that, if successful, will update existing instances with the new code/ applications.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nAlastair Kerr &amp; Bilal Hussain','Continuous Integration with Jenkins and GitHub','','inherit','open','open','','8-revision-v1','','','2015-08-20 08:43:55','2015-08-20 08:43:55','',8,'http://52.19.82.119/index.php/2015/08/20/8-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(48,9,'2015-08-20 08:44:25','2015-08-20 08:44:25','<strong>Scott</strong>\r\n\r\nYesterday Scott provisioned Tomcat agents with puppet and worked on linking with the Puppet master to complete the Continuous Delivery pipeline. He set up configrations and a symlink so that the Puppet master could integrate the application’s war file into the build.\r\n\r\nToday he will build a LAMP stack with puppet (minus MySQL as we will be using AWS RDS) for the agent nodes , and set up autoscaling / load balancer with James.\r\n\r\nBlockages: licensing issue for puppet, only 10 licenses for puppet enterprise. Have to manually revoke licenses for destroyed servers if we want to issue more<strong>\r\n</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Michael</strong>\r\n\r\nToday Michael will be setting up AWS CloudWatch for monitoring of the servers, and generally getting up to speed with the project<strong>\r\n</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>James</strong>\r\n\r\nYesterday James worked on the load balancer and autoscaling groups in AWS and got it working.\r\n\r\nToday he will be applying this to the final setup so that we have a more robust infrastructure.<strong>\r\n</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Bilal</strong>\r\n\r\nYesterday Bilal and Ali finished setting up Jenkins. Bilal worked on CodeDeploy but unfortunately found that we wouldn’t be able to use it. He also set up RDS with redundancy and tested this with the 2<sup>nd</sup> webapp.\r\n\r\nToday he will work on backup scripts for the SQL database and store these on S3 bucket.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Ali</strong>\r\n\r\nYesterday Ali and Bilal set up Jenkin’s final configurations for the Continuous Delivery pipeline, adding post build actions to send build artifacts to the puppet master for deployment. Ali also set up Vagrant to create a virtual environment with LAMP stack that developers can use to develop or test out code.\r\n\r\nToday he will make sure everything in Jenkins is configured properly, and take advantage of slack to see where else he can help out.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>John</strong>\r\n\r\nTBD','Standup Meeting 20th August 2015','','inherit','open','open','','45-revision-v1','','','2015-08-20 08:44:25','2015-08-20 08:44:25','',45,'http://52.19.82.119/index.php/2015/08/20/45-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(49,9,'2015-08-20 08:44:52','2015-08-20 08:44:52','While the Tomcat application has built in unit tests which are useful for allowing for a step of testing in the Continuous Integration environment (Jenkins), this cannot be said for the other web application. Unit Tests allow for builds to be verified before they are deployed, and this meant that we could have a fully automated Continuous Delivery pipeline without having to worry about faulty or broken builds being deployed to production servers. Without such a possibility for the 2nd application, we need a way for the developer(s) to test out their work in an environment mimicking the production environment so that they do not have to wait until their code is deployed live to find out if it will work.\r\n\r\n<img class=\"alignnone\" src=\"http://i.imgur.com/1P0thhr.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"1386\" height=\"754\" />\r\nThis comes in extension to whatever local testing they would do (e.g. in their IDE). Rather than spinning up a new online instance unnecessarily, the production environment can be replicated locally using a Virtual Machine (VM). However, a developer (presumably) would not want to spend lots of time configuring a server and installing all the packages they need, setting up the infrastructure etc. They want to spin something up that they can quickly and easily test their code on. For this reason, we decided it was a good idea to use Vagrant and Puppet to start up a Virtual Machine and bootstrap it with the necessary packages.\r\n\r\n<img class=\"alignnone\" src=\"http://i.imgur.com/x5r06TD.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"1182\" height=\"592\" />\r\n\r\nVagrant looks for and – if necessary – downloads the Ubuntu 14.04 vmbox from the internet at a given URL, and installs it before calling a bash script I wrote to install puppet. Vagrant is also configured to point to a ‘puppet’ folder with the manifests and modules (I used a LAMP stack module from puppetforge), which means that as soon as the process is finished the VM is setup with Apache2, MySQL and PHP. Furthermore, Vagrant was set up to configure a shared folder which the developer can place their website files in so that again, as soon as the VM is ready, their website/ web application is available rooted through to the host machine on localhost:8084.\r\n\r\n<img class=\"alignnone\" src=\"http://i.imgur.com/rwP9RZV.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"2248\" height=\"948\" />\r\n\r\nAlastair Kerr','Vagrant LAMP stack on Ubuntu 14.04 - Development/ Testing environment','','inherit','open','open','','33-revision-v1','','','2015-08-20 08:44:52','2015-08-20 08:44:52','',33,'http://52.19.82.119/index.php/2015/08/20/33-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(50,9,'2015-08-20 08:45:16','2015-08-20 08:45:16','Our initial plan was to use CodeDeploy, but after setting up the roles and profiles in AWS we found out that the Amazon accounts we had been provided with did not have access to the service. This was a big problem for us as CodeDeploy was a huge part of the Continuous Delivery pipeline and using it would have meant successful builds would swiftly and automatically be rolled out across our instances.\r\n\r\n<img class=\"alignnone\" src=\"http://i.imgur.com/Gn09XmN.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"582\" height=\"202\" />\r\n\r\nWithout this tool at our disposal we needed to find an alternative way. At this point we had fully implemented Continuous Integration with Jenkins for the Tomcat application, and so needed to work out how to get this build sent to our servers. We installed several Jenkins plugins to handle the post build steps; PostBuildScript allows for bash scripts to be executed as a post build action, and Artifact deployer allows for archived artifacts to be relocated to a more manageable location.\r\n\r\n<img class=\"alignnone\" src=\"http://i.imgur.com/fuUegLg.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"1844\" height=\"1156\" />\r\n\r\nThe specific implementation copies the archived build artifact (in the case of this Tomcat application, .war file) to a folder /builds/ owned by the Jenkins user, and then executes a simple scp transfer of the artifact to the Puppet master server (this involved configuring a limited permissions Jenkin user on the Puppet server with the public key from the Jenkins machine pasted into the authorized_keys for this new user). This meant that the Jenkins portion of the pipeline for this application was complete, with a push to the GitHub repository initiating a Jenkins build which, if successful, automatically sends the .war file to the Puppet master server which will then be used to provision the agent nodes.\r\n\r\n<img class=\"alignnone\" src=\"http://i.imgur.com/GZhTSYA.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"2058\" height=\"502\" />\r\n\r\nThis is not quite as elegant a solution as originally envisioned, but is necessary considering the limitations faced with the fact that we are not able to use CodeDeploy. The main issue with this setup is the increased overhead which is incurred and the unavoidable delay in updating agent nodes; while with CodeDeploy instances would begin to be updated immediately, with Puppet these updates will only apply when the agents check in to the master. By default this is every 30 minutes, but reducing this window will mean shorter turn-around times for updates at the cost of increased overhead. Nonetheless, we have successfully configured the backbones of a Continuous Delivery pipeline, and now must just finish up the Puppet configurations and then move on to other tasks.\r\n\r\nAlastair Kerr &amp; Bilal Hussain','Continuous Deployment Continued: CodeDeploy problem and workaround','','inherit','open','open','','28-revision-v1','','','2015-08-20 08:45:16','2015-08-20 08:45:16','',28,'http://52.19.82.119/index.php/2015/08/20/28-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(51,1,'2015-08-20 09:06:19','2015-08-20 09:06:19','<strong>Scott</strong>\n\nYesterday Scott provisioned Tomcat agents with puppet and worked on linking with the Puppet master to complete the Continuous Delivery pipeline. He set up configrations and a symlink so that the Puppet master could integrate the application’s war file into the build.\n\nToday he will build a LAMP stack with puppet (minus MySQL as we will be using AWS RDS) for the agent nodes , and set up autoscaling / load balancer with James.\n\nBlockages: licensing issue for puppet, only 10 licenses for puppet enterprise. Have to manually revoke licenses for destroyed servers if we want to issue more<strong>\n</strong>\n\n&nbsp;\n\n<strong>Michael</strong>\n\nToday Michael will be setting up AWS CloudWatch for monitoring of the servers, and generally getting up to speed with the project<strong>\n</strong>\n\n&nbsp;\n\n<strong>James</strong>\n\nYesterday James worked on the load balancer and autoscaling groups in AWS and got it working.\n\nToday he will be applying this to the final setup so that we have a more robust infrastructure.<strong>\n</strong>\n\n&nbsp;\n\n<strong>Bilal</strong>\n\nYesterday Bilal and Ali finished setting up Jenkins. Bilal worked on CodeDeploy but unfortunately found that we wouldn’t be able to use it. He also set up RDS with redundancy and tested this with the 2<sup>nd</sup> webapp.\n\nToday he will work on backup scripts for the SQL database and store these on S3 bucket.\n\n&nbsp;\n\n<strong>Ali</strong>\n\nYesterday Ali and Bilal set up Jenkin’s final configurations for the Continuous Delivery pipeline, adding post build actions to send build artifacts to the puppet master for deployment. Ali also set up Vagrant to create a virtual environment with LAMP stack that developers can use to develop or test out code.\n\nToday he will make sure everything in Jenkins is configured properly, and take advantage of slack to see where else he can help out.\n\n&nbsp;\n\n<strong>John</strong>\n\nToday I will assisting Michael with CloudWatch to','Standup Meeting 20th August 2015','','inherit','open','open','','45-autosave-v1','','','2015-08-20 09:06:19','2015-08-20 09:06:19','',45,'http://52.19.82.119/index.php/2015/08/20/45-autosave-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(52,1,'2015-08-20 09:07:17','2015-08-20 09:07:17','<strong>Scott</strong>\r\n\r\nYesterday Scott provisioned Tomcat agents with puppet and worked on linking with the Puppet master to complete the Continuous Delivery pipeline. He set up configrations and a symlink so that the Puppet master could integrate the application’s war file into the build.\r\n\r\nToday he will build a LAMP stack with puppet (minus MySQL as we will be using AWS RDS) for the agent nodes , and set up autoscaling / load balancer with James.\r\n\r\nBlockages: licensing issue for puppet, only 10 licenses for puppet enterprise. Have to manually revoke licenses for destroyed servers if we want to issue more<strong>\r\n</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Michael</strong>\r\n\r\nToday Michael will be setting up AWS CloudWatch for monitoring of the servers, and generally getting up to speed with the project<strong>\r\n</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>James</strong>\r\n\r\nYesterday James worked on the load balancer and autoscaling groups in AWS and got it working.\r\n\r\nToday he will be applying this to the final setup so that we have a more robust infrastructure.<strong>\r\n</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Bilal</strong>\r\n\r\nYesterday Bilal and Ali finished setting up Jenkins. Bilal worked on CodeDeploy but unfortunately found that we wouldn’t be able to use it. He also set up RDS with redundancy and tested this with the 2<sup>nd</sup> webapp.\r\n\r\nToday he will work on backup scripts for the SQL database and store these on S3 bucket.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Ali</strong>\r\n\r\nYesterday Ali and Bilal set up Jenkin’s final configurations for the Continuous Delivery pipeline, adding post build actions to send build artifacts to the puppet master for deployment. Ali also set up Vagrant to create a virtual environment with LAMP stack that developers can use to develop or test out code.\r\n\r\nToday he will make sure everything in Jenkins is configured properly, and take advantage of slack to see where else he can help out.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>John</strong>\r\n\r\nToday I will assisting Michael with CloudWatch which we will use to monitor the servers. I will also be updating myself on yesterdays tasks in preparation for Friday due to my absence.','Standup Meeting 20th August 2015','','inherit','open','open','','45-revision-v1','','','2015-08-20 09:07:17','2015-08-20 09:07:17','',45,'http://52.19.82.119/index.php/2015/08/20/45-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(53,1,'2015-08-20 11:11:18','2015-08-20 11:11:18','In this documentation I will discuss how I created a puppet module to automate the following activities :\n\n- install apache and PHP\n\n- Install MySQL\n\n- Create a database and a database user on MySQL for Wordpress\n\n- Install and configure WordPress\n\nIn order to perform these tasks I needed to spin up a ubuntu 14.04 virtual machine through AWS as well as having access to a sudo user.\n\n[embed]http://imgur.com/Mfckvyv[/embed]\n\nfirst step was to get the package downloaded using this command into the terminal via the ubuntu machine\n<pre class=\"code-pre \"><code>wget https://apt.puppetlabs.com/puppetlabs-release-trusty.deb\nsudo dpkg -i puppetlabs-release-trusty.deb</code></pre>\nonce this file had been downloaded I could then install puppet as well as checking the version which I had downloaded using these commands.\n<pre class=\"code-pre \"><code>sudo apt-get update\nsudo apt-get install puppet\n</code></pre>\n<pre class=\"code-pre \"><code>sudo puppet --version</code></pre>\nThe next stage was to install the puppet lab apache and mysql modules using the commands shown below.\n<pre class=\"code-pre \"><code>sudo puppet module install puppetlabs-apache\nsudo puppet module install puppetlabs-mysql</code></pre>\nonce I had completed this step I could then list the modules installed on the ubuntu machine as shown in the diagram below.\n\n[embed]http://imgur.com/zStRNq7[/embed]\n\nUpon the installation of the packages I then had to create a new directory in which I would store/create the modules. (mkdir MyModules)\n<pre class=\"code-pre \"><code>puppet module generate do-wordpress --skip-interview\n</code></pre>\n<pre class=\"code-pre \"><code>vi ~/MyModules/do-wordpress/metadata.json\n</code></pre>\nI then generated the modules and edited the metadata.json tag into the text editor, this has to be done because of a bug in puppet.\n\nThe next step was to start creating the manifest which would install Apache and PHP, I created the file through the \"vi\" text editor\n<pre class=\"code-pre \"><code>vi ~/MyModules/do-wordpress/manifests/web.pp\n</code></pre>\n<pre class=\"code-pre \"><code>class wordpress::web {\n\n    # Install Apache\n    class {\'apache\': \n        mpm_module =&gt; \'prefork\'\n    }\n\n    # Add support for PHP \n    class {\'::apache::mod::php\': }\n}</code></pre>\nin the screenshot above you can see that I added the classes as well as using a prefork via the multi-processing-module to increase compatibility with other modules.\n\nThe next step was to create a file to store configuration variables\n<pre class=\"code-pre \"><code>vi ~/MyModules/do-wordpress/manifests/conf.pp\n</code></pre>\n<pre class=\"code-pre \"><code>class wordpress::conf {\n    # You can change the values of these variables\n    # according to your preferences\n\n    $root_password = \'*********\'\n    $db_name = \'<span class=\"highlight\">wordpress</span>\'\n    $db_user = \'<span class=\"highlight\">wp</span>\'\n    $db_user_password = \'*******\'\n    $db_host = \'<span class=\"highlight\">localhost</span>\'\n\n    # Don\'t change the following variables\n\n    # This will evaluate to wp@localhost\n    $db_user_host = \"${db_user}@${db_host}\"\n\n    # This will evaluate to wp@localhost/wordpress.*\n    $db_user_host_db = \"${db_user}@${db_host}/${db_name}.*\"\n}</code></pre>\nAbove is the screenshot showing some of my test configuration.\n\nThe next stop was to create the manifest for MySQL, this manifest would perform the following operations;\n\n- Install the MySQL server\n\n- Sets the root password for MySQL Server\n\n- Creates a database for Wordpress\n\n- Creates a user for Wordpress\n\n- Grants privileges to the user to access the database\n\n- Install the MySQL client and bindings for various languages.\n<pre class=\"code-pre \"><code>class wordpress::db {\n\n    class { \'::mysql::server\':\n\n        # Set the root password\n        root_password =&gt; $wordpress::conf::root_password,\n\n        # Create the database\n        databases =&gt; {\n            \"${wordpress::conf::db_name}\" =&gt; {\n                ensure =&gt; \'present\',\n                charset =&gt; \'utf8\'\n            }\n        },\n\n        # Create the user\n        users =&gt; {\n            \"${wordpress::conf::db_user_host}\" =&gt; {\n                ensure =&gt; present,\n                password_hash =&gt; mysql_password(\"${wordpress::conf::db_user_password}\")\n            }\n        },\n\n        # Grant privileges to the user\n        grants =&gt; {\n            \"${wordpress::conf::db_user_host_db}\" =&gt; {\n                ensure     =&gt; \'present\',\n                options    =&gt; [\'GRANT\'],\n                privileges =&gt; [\'ALL\'],\n                table      =&gt; \"${wordpress::conf::db_name}.*\",\n                user       =&gt; \"${wordpress::conf::db_user_host}\",\n            }\n        },\n    }\n\n    # Install MySQL client and all bindings\n    class { \'::mysql::client\':\n        require =&gt; Class[\'::mysql::server\'],\n        bindings_enable =&gt; true\n    }\n}</code></pre>\nAll of the operations are performed through the classes ::mysql::server &amp; ::mysql::client\n\nThe following step is simply to download the latest version of Wordpress, in order to do this I had to create a new file in the directory \"MyModules\" this file was to be called files\n<pre class=\"code-pre \"><code>wget http://wordpress.org/latest.tar.gz</code></pre>\nabove is the command to download the latest Wordpress.\n\nThe next step was to create a template for the wp-config.php file, again I created a new file which I added to the do-wordpress folder, this file is named templates. I then moved in the /tmp folder and extracted the latest Wordpress files.\n<pre class=\"code-pre \"><code>tar -xvzf ~/MyModules/do-wordpress/files/latest.tar.gz  # Extract the tar\n</code></pre>\n<pre class=\"code-pre \"><code>cp /tmp/wordpress/wp-config-sample.php ~/MyModules/do-wordpress/templates/wp-config.php.erb\n</code></pre>\nI then cleaned up the /tmp folder\n<pre class=\"code-pre \"><code>rm -rf /tmp/wordpress  # Clean up\n</code></pre>\n<pre class=\"code-pre \"><code>vi ~/MyModules/do-wordpress/templates/wp-config.php.erb\n</code></pre>\nI then edited the wp-config.php.erb file.\n<pre class=\"code-pre \"><code>&lt;?php\ndefine(\'DB_NAME\', \'<span class=\"highlight\">&lt;%= scope.lookupvar(\'wordpress::conf::db_name\') %&gt;</span>\');\ndefine(\'DB_USER\', \'<span class=\"highlight\">&lt;%= scope.lookupvar(\'wordpress::conf::db_user\') %&gt;</span>\');\ndefine(\'DB_PASSWORD\', \'<span class=\"highlight\">&lt;%= scope.lookupvar(\'wordpress::conf::db_user_password\') %&gt;</span>\');\ndefine(\'DB_HOST\', \'<span class=\"highlight\">&lt;%= scope.lookupvar(\'wordpress::conf::db_host\') %&gt;</span>\');\ndefine(\'DB_CHARSET\', \'utf8\');\ndefine(\'DB_COLLATE\', \'\');\n\ndefine(\'AUTH_KEY\',         \'put your unique phrase here\');\ndefine(\'SECURE_AUTH_KEY\',  \'put your unique phrase here\');\ndefine(\'LOGGED_IN_KEY\',    \'put your unique phrase here\');\ndefine(\'NONCE_KEY\',        \'put your unique phrase here\');\ndefine(\'AUTH_SALT\',        \'put your unique phrase here\');\ndefine(\'SECURE_AUTH_SALT\', \'put your unique phrase here\');\ndefine(\'LOGGED_IN_SALT\',   \'put your unique phrase here\');\ndefine(\'NONCE_SALT\',       \'put your unique phrase here\');\n\n$table_prefix  = \'wp_\';\n\ndefine(\'WP_DEBUG\', false);\n\nif ( !defined(\'ABSPATH\') )\n    define(\'ABSPATH\', dirname(__FILE__) . \'/\');\n\nrequire_once(ABSPATH . \'wp-settings.php\');</code></pre>\nthe next step was to create the manifest for Wordpress\n<pre class=\"code-pre \"><code>vi ~/MyModules/do-wordpress/manifests/wp.pp\n</code></pre>\nI created this manifest to perform the following operations;\n\n- copy the contents of the Wordpress installation bundle to /var/www/ - this has to be done as apache has a default configuration which serves files to /var/www/\n\n- Generates the wp-config.php file using a template.\n<pre class=\"code-pre \"><code>class wordpress::wp {\n\n    # Copy the Wordpress bundle to /tmp\n    file { \'/tmp/latest.tar.gz\':\n        ensure =&gt; present,\n        source =&gt; \"puppet:///modules/wordpress/latest.tar.gz\"\n    }\n\n    # Extract the Wordpress bundle\n    exec { \'extract\':\n        cwd =&gt; \"/tmp\",\n        command =&gt; \"tar -xvzf latest.tar.gz\",\n        require =&gt; File[\'/tmp/latest.tar.gz\'],\n        path =&gt; [\'/bin\'],\n    }\n\n    # Copy to /var/www/\n    exec { \'copy\':\n        command =&gt; \"cp -r /tmp/wordpress/* /var/www/\",\n        require =&gt; Exec[\'extract\'],\n        path =&gt; [\'/bin\'],\n    }\n\n    # Generate the wp-config.php file using the template\n    file { \'/var/www/wp-config.php\':\n        ensure =&gt; present,\n        require =&gt; Exec[\'copy\'],\n        content =&gt; template(\"wordpress/wp-config.php.erb\")\n    }\n}</code></pre>\nthe next step was to create a .init.pp file, a manifest that integrates the other manifests.\n<pre class=\"code-pre \"><code>vi ~/MyModules/do-wordpress/manifests/init.pp\n</code></pre>\nthis is the code to enter into the text editor to alter the init.pp file.\n<pre class=\"code-pre \"><code>class wordpress {\n    # Load all variables\n    class { \'wordpress::conf\': }\n\n    # Install Apache and PHP\n    class { \'wordpress::web\': }\n\n    # Install MySQL\n    class { \'wordpress::db\': }\n\n    # Run Wordpress installation only after Apache is installed\n    class { \'wordpress::wp\': \n        require =&gt; Notify[\'Apache Installation Complete\']\n    }\n\n    # Display this message after MySQL installation is complete\n    notify { \'MySQL Installation Complete\':\n        require =&gt; Class[\'wordpress::db\']\n    }\n\n    # Display this message after Apache installation is complete\n    notify { \'Apache Installation Complete\':\n        require =&gt; Class[\'wordpress::web\']\n    }\n\n    # Display this message after Wordpress installation is complete\n    notify { \'Wordpress Installation Complete\':\n        require =&gt; Class[\'wordpress::wp\']\n    }\n}</code></pre>\nYou can see comments (#) about what each operation performs in the screenshot above.\n\nThe next step was to build the Wordpress module, this initial task i did was to change directory back to the \"MyModules\" folder, from here I then performed the following command.\n<pre class=\"code-pre \"><code>sudo puppet module build do-wordpress\n</code></pre>\nthis command built the Wordpress module. when entering this command I received the following message.\n<pre class=\"code-pre \"><code>Notice: Building /home/user/MyModules/do-wordpress for release\nModule built: /home/user/MyModules/do-wordpress/pkg/do-wordpress-0.1.0.tar.gz</code></pre>\nOnce I had built the Wordpress module I then began to install it using the following command.\n<pre class=\"code-pre \"><code>sudo puppet module install ~/MyModules/do-wordpress/pkg/do-wordpress-0.1.0.tar.gz\n</code></pre>\nTo test that the everything worked correctly I decided to use the module in a standalone manifest file to install Wordpress, to do this I entered the text editor for the appropriate file.\n<pre class=\"code-pre \"><code>vi /tmp/install-wp.pp\n</code></pre>\nI made the correct alterations to the file and then ran a puppet apply command.\n<pre class=\"code-pre \"><code>class { \'wordpress\':\n}</code></pre>\n<pre class=\"code-pre \"><code>sudo puppet apply /tmp/install-wp.pp</code></pre>\nOnce this was complete I then ran the IP address into the URL which then gave me access to the Wordpress service which we now use to document each task that we have done during the course of the D\n\n&nbsp;','Setting up a Puppet module to automate activities','','inherit','open','open','','1-autosave-v1','','','2015-08-20 11:11:18','2015-08-20 11:11:18','',1,'http://52.19.82.119/index.php/2015/08/20/1-autosave-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(54,9,'2015-08-20 09:18:25','2015-08-20 09:18:25','A core part of our overall system design is the Continuous Delivery pipeline, the primary software tools used being Jenkins and Amazon Web Services CodeDeploy. The overall aim of implementing these technologies was to allow for Continuous Deployment through linking remote GitHub repositories to a Jenkins server which builds the code, tests it, and – assuming these tests pass – instigates CodeDeploy to deploy the new build across the relevant AWS instances.\r\n\r\n<img class=\"alignnone\" src=\"http://i.imgur.com/ZInjSkH.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"2550\" height=\"1372\" />\r\n\r\nBilal and myself were responsible for this section of the project, and the first step in this process was to manually configure Jenkins. This helped us get a better understanding of how the software worked, and laid the foundations for a largely automated process later. Ubuntu 14.04 was the platform for this server, and setting up the CI platform necessitated installing Jenkins, git plugins, JDK7, maven and also apache2 (not necessary, but useful for enabling us to proxy Jenkins through to port 80 and using the public DNS, making the Jenkins interface accessible through the world wide web with a domain name assigned by Amazon). Lots of configurations needed to be made through the Jenkins interface, for example configuring the <em>MAVEN HOME</em> location so that the developer’s Java app could be built with Jenkins. Importantly, considering the globally accessible nature of this server, security configurations were made so that anonymous users have read only access and an administrator login allows for full privileges.\r\n\r\nA crucial requirement for facilitating this build was to link the relevant GitHub repository to the Jenkins server. Firstly, an SSH key was generated for the ‘jenkins’ user on the Jenkins server, which was used as a Deploy Key for the specific repository, a measure that was implemented through the settings in GitHub. This authentication was confirmed through the command line on the Jenkins server, as shown below.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>jenkins@ip-172-31-37-36:/usr/share/maven$ ssh-keygen</em>\r\n<em>Generating public/private rsa key pair.</em>\r\n<em>Enter file in which to save the key (/var/lib/jenkins/.ssh/id_rsa):</em>\r\n<em>Created directory \'/var/lib/jenkins/.ssh\'.</em>\r\n<em>Enter passphrase (empty for no passphrase):</em>\r\n<em>Enter same passphrase again:</em>\r\n<em>Your identification has been saved in /var/lib/jenkins/.ssh/id_rsa.</em>\r\n<em>Your public key has been saved in /var/lib/jenkins/.ssh/id_rsa.pub.</em>\r\n<em>The key fingerprint is:</em>\r\n<em>de:08:ce:0a:ee:a7:d4:d6:29:68:70:29:ee:14:6a:a9 jenkins@ip-172-31-37-36</em>\r\n<em>The key\'s randomart image is:</em>\r\n<em>+--[ RSA 2048]----+</em>\r\n<em>|                            |</em>\r\n<em>|                            |</em>\r\n<em>|                            |</em>\r\n<em>|    .                       |</em>\r\n<em>|o.o     .  S             |</em>\r\n<em>|o+oo + + o          |</em>\r\n<em>|.== + = o .            |</em>\r\n<em>|=+ o.o                  |</em>\r\n<em>|Eo+o.                   |</em>\r\n<em>+-----------------------+</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>jenkins@ip-172-31-37-36:/usr/share/maven$ ssh git@github.com</em>\r\n<em>PTY allocation request failed on channel 0</em>\r\n<em>Hi AKerr94/jenkins-test! You\'ve successfully authenticated, but GitHub does not provide shell access.</em>\r\n<em>Connection to github.com closed.</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nWith the Deploy Key successfully associated, the next measure we took was to setup a webhook. This means that an action on GitHub (such as a push to the repository) triggers an action, sending this information to the Jenkins server so that it can act appropriately (in our case we did indeed want Jenkins to automatically trigger a build following a push to the linked repository). This had to be setup in the repository’s settings with special links that Jenkins could handle, and on the Jenkins side the GitHub repository had to be linked along with authorization tokens for the associated account. Linking Jenkins and GitHub like this is a little more complex than other methods but doing so in this way means that Jenkins can build from a private repository, which is beneficial for example if developers do not want their code to be made public. Successful builds will need to trigger AWS CodeDeploy to deploy the application across our instances, and failed builds are logged, with monitoring available through the Jenkins interface and dashboards giving an overview of build health and allowing for an audit trail that can be used for error troubleshooting.\r\n\r\n<img class=\"alignnone\" src=\"http://i.imgur.com/DKPyFwU.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"2548\" height=\"1170\" />\r\n\r\nIn the case of a build failure Jenkins can also be configured to notify administrators or specific email accounts (such as the developer whose build is broken!). We tested this functionality with an email address for our team.\r\n\r\n<img class=\"alignnone\" src=\"http://i.imgur.com/33WFchd.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"1826\" height=\"928\" />\r\n\r\nWe tested that this configuration was working properly, as shown below.\r\n\r\n<img class=\"alignnone\" src=\"http://i.imgur.com/GrPYT9P.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"1652\" height=\"292\" />\r\n\r\nWith the Continuous Integration portion of the setup working, we then worked on automating the process. After initial issues with Puppet configurations, and, considering that we were already using the advanced options of AWS to provision Jenkins on our initial test servers with bash scripts, we decided to extend these with a more involved and all-round script that provisioned a Jenkins server pre-configured with many of the necessary plugins and setup options, for example dynamically inputting the initiated instances public DNS into the Apache configuration in order to allow for access over the web through the Amazon hostname (otherwise this would simply lead to the Apache default splashpage on port 80 rather than redirecting to the Jenkins interface).\r\n\r\n<img class=\"alignnone\" src=\"http://i.imgur.com/Yce5rxu.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"1532\" height=\"1010\" />\r\n\r\nWith this bash script a Jenkins server can be provisioned extremely quickly with AWS, and serves as a possible route for backup/ disaster recovery in the event of a server failure, although our main disaster recovery mechanism for the Jenkins server comes in the form of an AMI created from this final server configuration, which can be deployed as an AWS instance as needed. Therefore, this AMI would be our first port of call in the event of server failure, but with the bash script we have redundancy, so, for example, were AWS to fail, or, should we want to switch to a different service, we would not be reliant on these services and could provision another server with another provider.\r\n\r\nThe next steps we will take will be to setup CodeDeploy and connect this to Jenkins, so that successful builds will be automatically deployed across our infrastructure. In this manner, we will have achieved Continuous Deployment as pushes to the GitHub repository will initiate Jenkins builds that, if successful, will update existing instances with the new code/ applications.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nAlastair Kerr &amp; Bilal Hussain','Continuous Integration with Jenkins and GitHub','','inherit','open','open','','8-revision-v1','','','2015-08-20 09:18:25','2015-08-20 09:18:25','',8,'http://52.19.82.119/index.php/2015/08/20/8-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(55,9,'2015-08-20 10:40:05','2015-08-20 10:40:05','Today we did some simple email configurations in Jenkins to make sure individual developers could be notified of changes made breaking the build. We setup notifications for our team\'s devops gmail account as well as Selvyn\'s (who assumed the role of the developer in this project).\r\n\r\n<img class=\"alignnone\" src=\"http://i.imgur.com/dhJhNOt.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"1734\" height=\"574\" />\r\n\r\nShown working below:\r\n\r\n<img class=\"alignnone\" src=\"http://i.imgur.com/kAnAKbR.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"2510\" height=\"482\" />\r\n\r\nThe email notifies you of the problem and sends a link.\r\n\r\n<img class=\"alignnone\" src=\"http://i.imgur.com/7T8NwVi.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"2014\" height=\"394\" />\r\n\r\nFollowing the link takes you to the Jenkins interface with information regarding the unstable/ failed build.\r\n\r\n<img class=\"alignnone\" src=\"http://i.imgur.com/v9dr90Q.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"1520\" height=\"526\" />\r\n\r\nClicking on the commit link takes you to the change record on the GitHub repository to see what changes were made to the repository that caused this build to fail.\r\n\r\n<img class=\"alignnone\" src=\"http://i.imgur.com/6wSuQQq.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"1904\" height=\"856\" />\r\n\r\nAs can be seen above, Selvyn\'s change to the code meant that the wrong date was being sent back, and so the Unit tests he had written to test this part of the code failed, causing the build to be marked unstable. This triggered the emails to be sent out, and also meant that the build was not deployed to the Puppet Master.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;','Jenkins Notifications','','publish','open','open','','jenkins-notifications','','','2015-08-20 11:11:28','2015-08-20 11:11:28','',0,'http://52.19.82.119/?p=55',0,'post','',0),(56,9,'2015-08-20 10:40:05','2015-08-20 10:40:05','Today we did some simple email configurations in Jenkins to make sure individual developers could be notified of changes made breaking the build. We setup notifications for our team\'s devops gmail account as well as Selvyn\'s (who assumed the role of the developer in this project).\r\n\r\n<img class=\"alignnone\" src=\"http://i.imgur.com/dhJhNOt.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"1734\" height=\"574\" />\r\n\r\nShown working below:\r\n\r\n<img class=\"alignnone\" src=\"http://i.imgur.com/kAnAKbR.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"2510\" height=\"482\" />\r\n\r\nThe email notifies you of the problem and sends a link.\r\n\r\n<img class=\"alignnone\" src=\"http://i.imgur.com/7T8NwVi.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"2014\" height=\"394\" />\r\n\r\nFollowing the link takes you to the Jenkins interface with information regarding the unstable/ failed build.\r\n\r\n<img class=\"alignnone\" src=\"http://i.imgur.com/v9dr90Q.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"1520\" height=\"526\" />\r\n\r\nClicking on the commit link takes you to the change record on the GitHub repository to see what changes were made to the repository that caused this build to fail.\r\n\r\n<img class=\"alignnone\" src=\"http://i.imgur.com/6wSuQQq.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"1904\" height=\"856\" />\r\n\r\nAs can be seen above, Selvyn\'s change to the code meant that the wrong date was being sent back, and so the Unit tests he had written to test this part of the code failed, causing the build to be marked unstable. This triggered the emails to be sent out, and also meant that the build was not deployed to the Puppet Master.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;','Jenkins Notifications','','inherit','open','open','','55-revision-v1','','','2015-08-20 10:40:05','2015-08-20 10:40:05','',55,'http://52.19.82.119/index.php/2015/08/20/55-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(57,9,'2015-08-20 10:40:17','2015-08-20 10:40:17','Today we did some simple email configurations in Jenkins to make sure individual developers could be notified of changes made breaking the build. We setup notifications for our team\'s devops gmail account as well as Selvyn\'s (who assumed the role of the developer in this project).\r\n\r\n<img class=\"alignnone\" src=\"http://i.imgur.com/dhJhNOt.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"1734\" height=\"574\" />\r\n\r\nShown working below:\r\n\r\n<img class=\"alignnone\" src=\"http://i.imgur.com/kAnAKbR.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"2510\" height=\"482\" />\r\n\r\nThe email notifies you of the problem and sends a link.\r\n\r\n<img class=\"alignnone\" src=\"http://i.imgur.com/7T8NwVi.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"2014\" height=\"394\" />\r\n\r\nFollowing the link takes you to the Jenkins interface with information regarding the unstable/ failed build.\r\n\r\n<img class=\"alignnone\" src=\"http://i.imgur.com/v9dr90Q.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"1520\" height=\"526\" />\r\n\r\nClicking on the commit link takes you to the change record on the GitHub repository to see what changes were made to the repository that caused this build to fail.\r\n\r\n<img class=\"alignnone\" src=\"http://i.imgur.com/6wSuQQq.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"1904\" height=\"856\" />\r\n\r\nAs can be seen above, Selvyn\'s change to the code meant that the wrong date was being sent back, and so the Unit tests he had written to test this part of the code failed, causing the build to be marked unstable. This triggered the emails to be sent out, and also meant that the build was not deployed to the Puppet Master.\r\n\r\nAlastair Kerr\r\n\r\n&nbsp;','Jenkins Notifications','','inherit','open','open','','55-revision-v1','','','2015-08-20 10:40:17','2015-08-20 10:40:17','',55,'http://52.19.82.119/index.php/2015/08/20/55-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(58,9,'2015-08-20 10:50:02','2015-08-20 10:50:02','Today we did some simple email configurations in Jenkins to make sure individual developers could be notified of changes made breaking the build. We setup notifications for our team\'s devops gmail account as well as Selvyn\'s (who assumed the role of the developer in this project).\r\n\r\n<img class=\"alignnone\" src=\"http://i.imgur.com/dhJhNOt.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"1734\" height=\"574\" />\r\n\r\nShown working below:\r\n\r\n<img class=\"alignnone\" src=\"http://i.imgur.com/kAnAKbR.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"2510\" height=\"482\" />\r\n\r\nThe email notifies you of the problem and sends a link.\r\n\r\n<img class=\"alignnone\" src=\"http://i.imgur.com/7T8NwVi.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"2014\" height=\"394\" />\r\n\r\nFollowing the link takes you to the Jenkins interface with information regarding the unstable/ failed build.\r\n\r\n<img class=\"alignnone\" src=\"http://i.imgur.com/v9dr90Q.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"1520\" height=\"526\" />\r\n\r\nClicking on the commit link takes you to the change record on the GitHub repository to see what changes were made to the repository that caused this build to fail.\r\n\r\n<img class=\"alignnone\" src=\"http://i.imgur.com/6wSuQQq.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"1904\" height=\"856\" />\r\n\r\nAs can be seen above, Selvyn\'s change to the code meant that the wrong date was being sent back, and so the Unit tests he had written to test this part of the code failed, causing the build to be marked unstable. This triggered the emails to be sent out, and also meant that the build was not deployed to the Puppet Master.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;','Jenkins Notifications','','inherit','open','open','','55-revision-v1','','','2015-08-20 10:50:02','2015-08-20 10:50:02','',55,'http://52.19.82.119/index.php/2015/08/20/55-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(59,9,'2015-08-20 11:11:12','2015-08-20 11:11:12','Today we did some simple email configurations in Jenkins to make sure individual developers could be notified of changes made breaking the build. We setup notifications for our team\'s devops gmail account as well as Selvyn\'s (who assumed the role of the developer in this project).\r\n\r\n<img class=\"alignnone\" src=\"http://i.imgur.com/dhJhNOt.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"1734\" height=\"574\" />\r\n\r\nShown working below:\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<img class=\"alignnone\" src=\"http://i.imgur.com/kAnAKbR.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"2510\" height=\"482\" />\r\n\r\nThe email notifies you of the problem and sends a link.\r\n\r\n<img class=\"alignnone\" src=\"http://i.imgur.com/7T8NwVi.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"2014\" height=\"394\" />\r\n\r\nFollowing the link takes you to the Jenkins interface with information regarding the unstable/ failed build.\r\n\r\n<img class=\"alignnone\" src=\"http://i.imgur.com/v9dr90Q.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"1520\" height=\"526\" />\r\n\r\nClicking on the commit link takes you to the change record on the GitHub repository to see what changes were made to the repository that caused this build to fail.\r\n\r\n<img class=\"alignnone\" src=\"http://i.imgur.com/6wSuQQq.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"1904\" height=\"856\" />\r\n\r\nAs can be seen above, Selvyn\'s change to the code meant that the wrong date was being sent back, and so the Unit tests he had written to test this part of the code failed, causing the build to be marked unstable. This triggered the emails to be sent out, and also meant that the build was not deployed to the Puppet Master.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;','Jenkins Notifications','','inherit','open','open','','55-revision-v1','','','2015-08-20 11:11:12','2015-08-20 11:11:12','',55,'http://52.19.82.119/index.php/2015/08/20/55-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(60,9,'2015-08-20 11:11:28','2015-08-20 11:11:28','Today we did some simple email configurations in Jenkins to make sure individual developers could be notified of changes made breaking the build. We setup notifications for our team\'s devops gmail account as well as Selvyn\'s (who assumed the role of the developer in this project).\r\n\r\n<img class=\"alignnone\" src=\"http://i.imgur.com/dhJhNOt.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"1734\" height=\"574\" />\r\n\r\nShown working below:\r\n\r\n<img class=\"alignnone\" src=\"http://i.imgur.com/kAnAKbR.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"2510\" height=\"482\" />\r\n\r\nThe email notifies you of the problem and sends a link.\r\n\r\n<img class=\"alignnone\" src=\"http://i.imgur.com/7T8NwVi.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"2014\" height=\"394\" />\r\n\r\nFollowing the link takes you to the Jenkins interface with information regarding the unstable/ failed build.\r\n\r\n<img class=\"alignnone\" src=\"http://i.imgur.com/v9dr90Q.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"1520\" height=\"526\" />\r\n\r\nClicking on the commit link takes you to the change record on the GitHub repository to see what changes were made to the repository that caused this build to fail.\r\n\r\n<img class=\"alignnone\" src=\"http://i.imgur.com/6wSuQQq.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"1904\" height=\"856\" />\r\n\r\nAs can be seen above, Selvyn\'s change to the code meant that the wrong date was being sent back, and so the Unit tests he had written to test this part of the code failed, causing the build to be marked unstable. This triggered the emails to be sent out, and also meant that the build was not deployed to the Puppet Master.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;','Jenkins Notifications','','inherit','open','open','','55-revision-v1','','','2015-08-20 11:11:28','2015-08-20 11:11:28','',55,'http://52.19.82.119/index.php/2015/08/20/55-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(61,1,'2015-08-20 11:12:21','2015-08-20 11:12:21','In this documentation I will discuss how I created a puppet module to automate the following activities :\r\n\r\n- install apache and PHP\r\n\r\n- Install MySQL\r\n\r\n- Create a database and a database user on MySQL for Wordpress\r\n\r\n- Install and configure WordPress\r\n\r\nIn order to perform these tasks I needed to spin up a ubuntu 14.04 virtual machine through AWS as well as having access to a sudo user.\r\n\r\n[embed]http://imgur.com/Mfckvyv[/embed]\r\n\r\nfirst step was to get the package downloaded using this command into the terminal via the ubuntu machine\r\n<pre class=\"code-pre \"><code>wget https://apt.puppetlabs.com/puppetlabs-release-trusty.deb\r\nsudo dpkg -i puppetlabs-release-trusty.deb</code></pre>\r\nonce this file had been downloaded I could then install puppet as well as checking the version which I had downloaded using these commands.\r\n<pre class=\"code-pre \"><code>sudo apt-get update\r\nsudo apt-get install puppet\r\n</code></pre>\r\n<pre class=\"code-pre \"><code>sudo puppet --version</code></pre>\r\nThe next stage was to install the puppet lab apache and mysql modules using the commands shown below.\r\n<pre class=\"code-pre \"><code>sudo puppet module install puppetlabs-apache\r\nsudo puppet module install puppetlabs-mysql</code></pre>\r\nonce I had completed this step I could then list the modules installed on the ubuntu machine as shown in the diagram below.\r\n\r\n[embed]http://imgur.com/zStRNq7[/embed]\r\n\r\nUpon the installation of the packages I then had to create a new directory in which I would store/create the modules. (mkdir MyModules)\r\n<pre class=\"code-pre \"><code>puppet module generate do-wordpress --skip-interview\r\n</code></pre>\r\n<pre class=\"code-pre \"><code>vi ~/MyModules/do-wordpress/metadata.json\r\n</code></pre>\r\nI then generated the modules and edited the metadata.json tag into the text editor, this has to be done because of a bug in puppet.\r\n\r\nThe next step was to start creating the manifest which would install Apache and PHP, I created the file through the \"vi\" text editor\r\n<pre class=\"code-pre \"><code>vi ~/MyModules/do-wordpress/manifests/web.pp\r\n</code></pre>\r\n<pre class=\"code-pre \"><code>class wordpress::web {\r\n\r\n    # Install Apache\r\n    class {\'apache\': \r\n        mpm_module =&gt; \'prefork\'\r\n    }\r\n\r\n    # Add support for PHP \r\n    class {\'::apache::mod::php\': }\r\n}</code></pre>\r\nin the screenshot above you can see that I added the classes as well as using a prefork via the multi-processing-module to increase compatibility with other modules.\r\n\r\nThe next step was to create a file to store configuration variables\r\n<pre class=\"code-pre \"><code>vi ~/MyModules/do-wordpress/manifests/conf.pp\r\n</code></pre>\r\n<pre class=\"code-pre \"><code>class wordpress::conf {\r\n    # You can change the values of these variables\r\n    # according to your preferences\r\n\r\n    $root_password = \'*********\'\r\n    $db_name = \'<span class=\"highlight\">wordpress</span>\'\r\n    $db_user = \'<span class=\"highlight\">wp</span>\'\r\n    $db_user_password = \'*******\'\r\n    $db_host = \'<span class=\"highlight\">localhost</span>\'\r\n\r\n    # Don\'t change the following variables\r\n\r\n    # This will evaluate to wp@localhost\r\n    $db_user_host = \"${db_user}@${db_host}\"\r\n\r\n    # This will evaluate to wp@localhost/wordpress.*\r\n    $db_user_host_db = \"${db_user}@${db_host}/${db_name}.*\"\r\n}</code></pre>\r\nAbove is the screenshot showing some of my test configuration.\r\n\r\nThe next stop was to create the manifest for MySQL, this manifest would perform the following operations;\r\n\r\n- Install the MySQL server\r\n\r\n- Sets the root password for MySQL Server\r\n\r\n- Creates a database for Wordpress\r\n\r\n- Creates a user for Wordpress\r\n\r\n- Grants privileges to the user to access the database\r\n\r\n- Install the MySQL client and bindings for various languages.\r\n<pre class=\"code-pre \"><code>class wordpress::db {\r\n\r\n    class { \'::mysql::server\':\r\n\r\n        # Set the root password\r\n        root_password =&gt; $wordpress::conf::root_password,\r\n\r\n        # Create the database\r\n        databases =&gt; {\r\n            \"${wordpress::conf::db_name}\" =&gt; {\r\n                ensure =&gt; \'present\',\r\n                charset =&gt; \'utf8\'\r\n            }\r\n        },\r\n\r\n        # Create the user\r\n        users =&gt; {\r\n            \"${wordpress::conf::db_user_host}\" =&gt; {\r\n                ensure =&gt; present,\r\n                password_hash =&gt; mysql_password(\"${wordpress::conf::db_user_password}\")\r\n            }\r\n        },\r\n\r\n        # Grant privileges to the user\r\n        grants =&gt; {\r\n            \"${wordpress::conf::db_user_host_db}\" =&gt; {\r\n                ensure     =&gt; \'present\',\r\n                options    =&gt; [\'GRANT\'],\r\n                privileges =&gt; [\'ALL\'],\r\n                table      =&gt; \"${wordpress::conf::db_name}.*\",\r\n                user       =&gt; \"${wordpress::conf::db_user_host}\",\r\n            }\r\n        },\r\n    }\r\n\r\n    # Install MySQL client and all bindings\r\n    class { \'::mysql::client\':\r\n        require =&gt; Class[\'::mysql::server\'],\r\n        bindings_enable =&gt; true\r\n    }\r\n}</code></pre>\r\nAll of the operations are performed through the classes ::mysql::server &amp; ::mysql::client\r\n\r\nThe following step is simply to download the latest version of Wordpress, in order to do this I had to create a new file in the directory \"MyModules\" this file was to be called files\r\n<pre class=\"code-pre \"><code>wget http://wordpress.org/latest.tar.gz</code></pre>\r\nabove is the command to download the latest Wordpress.\r\n\r\nThe next step was to create a template for the wp-config.php file, again I created a new file which I added to the do-wordpress folder, this file is named templates. I then moved in the /tmp folder and extracted the latest Wordpress files.\r\n<pre class=\"code-pre \"><code>tar -xvzf ~/MyModules/do-wordpress/files/latest.tar.gz  # Extract the tar\r\n</code></pre>\r\n<pre class=\"code-pre \"><code>cp /tmp/wordpress/wp-config-sample.php ~/MyModules/do-wordpress/templates/wp-config.php.erb\r\n</code></pre>\r\nI then cleaned up the /tmp folder\r\n<pre class=\"code-pre \"><code>rm -rf /tmp/wordpress  # Clean up\r\n</code></pre>\r\n<pre class=\"code-pre \"><code>vi ~/MyModules/do-wordpress/templates/wp-config.php.erb\r\n</code></pre>\r\nI then edited the wp-config.php.erb file.\r\n<pre class=\"code-pre \"><code>&lt;?php\r\ndefine(\'DB_NAME\', \'<span class=\"highlight\">&lt;%= scope.lookupvar(\'wordpress::conf::db_name\') %&gt;</span>\');\r\ndefine(\'DB_USER\', \'<span class=\"highlight\">&lt;%= scope.lookupvar(\'wordpress::conf::db_user\') %&gt;</span>\');\r\ndefine(\'DB_PASSWORD\', \'<span class=\"highlight\">&lt;%= scope.lookupvar(\'wordpress::conf::db_user_password\') %&gt;</span>\');\r\ndefine(\'DB_HOST\', \'<span class=\"highlight\">&lt;%= scope.lookupvar(\'wordpress::conf::db_host\') %&gt;</span>\');\r\ndefine(\'DB_CHARSET\', \'utf8\');\r\ndefine(\'DB_COLLATE\', \'\');\r\n\r\ndefine(\'AUTH_KEY\',         \'put your unique phrase here\');\r\ndefine(\'SECURE_AUTH_KEY\',  \'put your unique phrase here\');\r\ndefine(\'LOGGED_IN_KEY\',    \'put your unique phrase here\');\r\ndefine(\'NONCE_KEY\',        \'put your unique phrase here\');\r\ndefine(\'AUTH_SALT\',        \'put your unique phrase here\');\r\ndefine(\'SECURE_AUTH_SALT\', \'put your unique phrase here\');\r\ndefine(\'LOGGED_IN_SALT\',   \'put your unique phrase here\');\r\ndefine(\'NONCE_SALT\',       \'put your unique phrase here\');\r\n\r\n$table_prefix  = \'wp_\';\r\n\r\ndefine(\'WP_DEBUG\', false);\r\n\r\nif ( !defined(\'ABSPATH\') )\r\n    define(\'ABSPATH\', dirname(__FILE__) . \'/\');\r\n\r\nrequire_once(ABSPATH . \'wp-settings.php\');</code></pre>\r\nthe next step was to create the manifest for Wordpress\r\n<pre class=\"code-pre \"><code>vi ~/MyModules/do-wordpress/manifests/wp.pp\r\n</code></pre>\r\nI created this manifest to perform the following operations;\r\n\r\n- copy the contents of the Wordpress installation bundle to /var/www/ - this has to be done as apache has a default configuration which serves files to /var/www/\r\n\r\n- Generates the wp-config.php file using a template.\r\n<pre class=\"code-pre \"><code>class wordpress::wp {\r\n\r\n    # Copy the Wordpress bundle to /tmp\r\n    file { \'/tmp/latest.tar.gz\':\r\n        ensure =&gt; present,\r\n        source =&gt; \"puppet:///modules/wordpress/latest.tar.gz\"\r\n    }\r\n\r\n    # Extract the Wordpress bundle\r\n    exec { \'extract\':\r\n        cwd =&gt; \"/tmp\",\r\n        command =&gt; \"tar -xvzf latest.tar.gz\",\r\n        require =&gt; File[\'/tmp/latest.tar.gz\'],\r\n        path =&gt; [\'/bin\'],\r\n    }\r\n\r\n    # Copy to /var/www/\r\n    exec { \'copy\':\r\n        command =&gt; \"cp -r /tmp/wordpress/* /var/www/\",\r\n        require =&gt; Exec[\'extract\'],\r\n        path =&gt; [\'/bin\'],\r\n    }\r\n\r\n    # Generate the wp-config.php file using the template\r\n    file { \'/var/www/wp-config.php\':\r\n        ensure =&gt; present,\r\n        require =&gt; Exec[\'copy\'],\r\n        content =&gt; template(\"wordpress/wp-config.php.erb\")\r\n    }\r\n}</code></pre>\r\nthe next step was to create a .init.pp file, a manifest that integrates the other manifests.\r\n<pre class=\"code-pre \"><code>vi ~/MyModules/do-wordpress/manifests/init.pp\r\n</code></pre>\r\nthis is the code to enter into the text editor to alter the init.pp file.\r\n<pre class=\"code-pre \"><code>class wordpress {\r\n    # Load all variables\r\n    class { \'wordpress::conf\': }\r\n\r\n    # Install Apache and PHP\r\n    class { \'wordpress::web\': }\r\n\r\n    # Install MySQL\r\n    class { \'wordpress::db\': }\r\n\r\n    # Run Wordpress installation only after Apache is installed\r\n    class { \'wordpress::wp\': \r\n        require =&gt; Notify[\'Apache Installation Complete\']\r\n    }\r\n\r\n    # Display this message after MySQL installation is complete\r\n    notify { \'MySQL Installation Complete\':\r\n        require =&gt; Class[\'wordpress::db\']\r\n    }\r\n\r\n    # Display this message after Apache installation is complete\r\n    notify { \'Apache Installation Complete\':\r\n        require =&gt; Class[\'wordpress::web\']\r\n    }\r\n\r\n    # Display this message after Wordpress installation is complete\r\n    notify { \'Wordpress Installation Complete\':\r\n        require =&gt; Class[\'wordpress::wp\']\r\n    }\r\n}</code></pre>\r\nYou can see comments (#) about what each operation performs in the screenshot above.\r\n\r\nThe next step was to build the Wordpress module, this initial task i did was to change directory back to the \"MyModules\" folder, from here I then performed the following command.\r\n<pre class=\"code-pre \"><code>sudo puppet module build do-wordpress\r\n</code></pre>\r\nthis command built the Wordpress module. when entering this command I received the following message.\r\n<pre class=\"code-pre \"><code>Notice: Building /home/user/MyModules/do-wordpress for release\r\nModule built: /home/user/MyModules/do-wordpress/pkg/do-wordpress-0.1.0.tar.gz</code></pre>\r\nOnce I had built the Wordpress module I then began to install it using the following command.\r\n<pre class=\"code-pre \"><code>sudo puppet module install ~/MyModules/do-wordpress/pkg/do-wordpress-0.1.0.tar.gz\r\n</code></pre>\r\nTo test that the everything worked correctly I decided to use the module in a standalone manifest file to install Wordpress, to do this I entered the text editor for the appropriate file.\r\n<pre class=\"code-pre \"><code>vi /tmp/install-wp.pp\r\n</code></pre>\r\nI made the correct alterations to the file and then ran a puppet apply command.\r\n<pre class=\"code-pre \"><code>class { \'wordpress\':\r\n}</code></pre>\r\n<pre class=\"code-pre \"><code>sudo puppet apply /tmp/install-wp.pp</code></pre>\r\nOnce this was complete I then ran the IP address into the URL which then gave me access to the Wordpress service which we now use to document each task that we have done during the course of the DevOps case study 2015.\r\n\r\nThe final stage was to then add my team as users so that they could also document what they had done as part of the team, I assigned them all administrative roles so that they had full access to whatever they needed.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;','Setting up a Puppet module to automate activities','','inherit','open','open','','1-revision-v1','','','2015-08-20 11:12:21','2015-08-20 11:12:21','',1,'http://52.19.82.119/index.php/2015/08/20/1-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(62,9,'2015-08-20 13:38:35','2015-08-20 13:38:35','In the end the final infrastructure matches our initial plans very closely. One major difference however is the lack of CodeDeploy due to aforementioned problems with our access to this service with our AWS student accounts. Because of this, Jenkins is configured to deploy the Tomcat application file to the Puppet Master which then uses this to provision the agents, rather than having Jenkins trigger CodeDeploy to roll out updates builds across the instances.\r\n\r\nBelow is a photo of our whiteboard where we planned out the infrastructure initially.\r\n\r\n<img class=\"alignnone\" src=\"http://i.imgur.com/ZS2mLIe.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"5312\" height=\"2988\" />\r\n\r\nA sketch of our planned infrastructure once we realised we couldn\'t use CodeDeploy looked like this:\r\n\r\n<img class=\"alignnone\" src=\"http://i.imgur.com/qxSL29h.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"5312\" height=\"2988\" />\r\n\r\nAnd finally here is a more clear, digital version of this flow diagram which shows how the various services and tools connect and communicate with each other.\r\n\r\n<img class=\"alignnone\" src=\"http://i.imgur.com/Bs1guZY.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"992\" height=\"633\" />','Infrastructure Diagrams and Plans','','publish','open','open','','infrastructure-diagrams-and-plans','','','2015-08-20 13:38:35','2015-08-20 13:38:35','',0,'http://52.19.82.119/?p=62',0,'post','',0),(63,9,'2015-08-20 13:38:35','2015-08-20 13:38:35','In the end the final infrastructure matches our initial plans very closely. One major difference however is the lack of CodeDeploy due to aforementioned problems with our access to this service with our AWS student accounts. Because of this, Jenkins is configured to deploy the Tomcat application file to the Puppet Master which then uses this to provision the agents, rather than having Jenkins trigger CodeDeploy to roll out updates builds across the instances.\r\n\r\nBelow is a photo of our whiteboard where we planned out the infrastructure initially.\r\n\r\n<img class=\"alignnone\" src=\"http://i.imgur.com/ZS2mLIe.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"5312\" height=\"2988\" />\r\n\r\nA sketch of our planned infrastructure once we realised we couldn\'t use CodeDeploy looked like this:\r\n\r\n<img class=\"alignnone\" src=\"http://i.imgur.com/qxSL29h.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"5312\" height=\"2988\" />\r\n\r\nAnd finally here is a more clear, digital version of this flow diagram which shows how the various services and tools connect and communicate with each other.\r\n\r\n<img class=\"alignnone\" src=\"http://i.imgur.com/Bs1guZY.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"992\" height=\"633\" />','Infrastructure Diagrams and Plans','','inherit','open','open','','62-revision-v1','','','2015-08-20 13:38:35','2015-08-20 13:38:35','',62,'http://52.19.82.119/index.php/2015/08/20/62-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(64,2,'2015-08-20 13:51:15','2015-08-20 13:51:15','We as a team decided to use AWS RDS MYSQL service as it is simple and integrated with Amazon Web Services. AWS allows the option to spread the databases through multiple sites by using the concept of master and slaves. The master copy is the main database instance and the slaves are replicating the database. Hence if the main database goes down, the slave takes over until the master is brought back up again.\r\n\r\nTo create RDS, we have to select RDS service the AWS Dashboard:\r\n\r\n<img class=\"alignnone\" src=\"http://i.imgur.com/i3D034w.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"838\" height=\"514\" />\r\n\r\nClick on Launch DB Instance to create a new instance\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<img class=\"alignnone\" src=\"http://i.imgur.com/yNuwEF8.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"1354\" height=\"494\" />\r\n\r\nThis will prompt the user to select an option to what type of Relation Database System the user would like to select. For this case, I selected MySQL as the developer\'s application requirement was built upon MySQL platform. Once it is selected, the user is prompted with whether to use the Multi AZ deployment service or to be used on one location. I selected MultiAZ deployment as this ensures my database is secure so for instance if my master database located in Ireland data centre site A goes down, the database is replicated to another Site e.g. Site B which will pick up the jobs until the Site A database comes back up.\r\n\r\nOnce that is complete, final step is to configure the instance specifications and settings. This includes, attaching a pre-configured policy, Database Instance Identifier, Master username and password. The next option takes the configurations further to network, security, backups and Database options which includes giving it a name. Most of it is by default pre-configured unless in some circumstances it needs to be changed.\r\n\r\nFinally once the instance is completed, the new instance starts to create itself and appears on the RDS dashboard.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>MYSQL Monitor</strong>\r\n\r\nTo integrate with the database, I need to have an instance where I can run MySQL utilities which can then be used to connect to the RDS database on amazon using the endpoint. The endpoint is a URL which runs over https and can be found in the Database information:\r\n\r\n<img class=\"alignnone\" src=\"http://i.imgur.com/jPyvXJu.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"1812\" height=\"720\" />\r\n\r\nOnce the endpoint is noted, I launched a new EC2 instance which was used to install mysql locally. Once it was installed, I ran the following command to access mysql:\r\n<blockquote>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\">mysql -u admin -P 3306 -h skydevop2015database.czk330ifgg3j.eu-west-1.rds.amazonaws.com -p**************</p>\r\n</blockquote>\r\nonce in mysql monitor, a script which was provided to us by the developer was executed to create the table and add the datasets into the table. Once the table was inserted, it was time to test it on the php app to ensure that the application is able to select datasets dynamically.\r\n\r\nTo test it, I created a new test EC2 instance which was used to the deploy the application running on LAMP stack except the MYSQL was not really needed as we have a RDS instance running in Amazon Cloud. The only thing that needed modifying was defining the php file to integrate with RDS instance. To do this, I had to change the file useful.php:\r\n\r\n<img class=\"alignnone\" src=\"http://i.imgur.com/IsnYyAB.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"1810\" height=\"258\" />\r\n\r\nOnce this was complete, the webapp was successfully able to access the data from the users table so they could be used to log in.','RDS AWS MYSQL','','inherit','open','open','','35-revision-v1','','','2015-08-20 13:51:15','2015-08-20 13:51:15','',35,'http://52.19.82.119/index.php/2015/08/20/35-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(65,2,'2015-08-20 14:15:44','2015-08-20 14:15:44','We are using 2 databases for this system. One is the local database running on LAMP stack for Word Press and we have the RDS cloud MySQL database running on Amazon Web services for the php web application.\r\n\r\n<strong>RDS Backup Script</strong>\r\n\r\nI created a backup script which creates folders using the day\'s date and dumps SQL tables into a file which is named after the time it is created. The script first checks if there is directory for the day. If not it first creates a directory and dumps the SQL data into it. If the directory already exists, it skips creating it and only dumps the data into the directory on the current date. The shell command to dump sql data is following:\r\n<blockquote>mysqldump --user ${USER} -p${PASS} --host ${DBSERVER} --databases ${DATABASE} &gt; $BACKUPDIRPATH$DATE/$FILE</blockquote>\r\n<strong>Logs</strong>\r\n\r\nTo ensure we are able to troubleshoot if the backups are not running. I am saving confirmation of each instance into a log file. The log file writes and confirms that steps are being undertaken.\r\n\r\n<strong>Cronjob</strong>\r\n\r\nCrontab is a linux in-built scheduler which runs scripts on a timely basis. This is the way to automate the script to run every hour. To do this, following commands were used:\r\n<blockquote>crontab -e # To edit crontab file\r\n\r\n0 * * * * /PATH-TO-SCRIPT.sh # insert this to ensure it runs hourly\r\n\r\ncrontab -l # To list the cronjobs currently being executed</blockquote>\r\nScript Screenshot:\r\n\r\n<img class=\"alignnone\" src=\"http://i.imgur.com/HFwB454.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"665\" height=\"403\" />\r\n\r\n<strong>S3 Bucket</strong>\r\n\r\nAll the backups are automatically stored to S3 bucket on Amazon Web Services. To do that, I had to install a s3 tool called s3cmd. This command is used to list,delete,create and put buckets and folders on S3. I used this tool in the script to run automatically once it has created the backups and use the put command to place them.\r\n<blockquote>/home/ec2-user/bin/s3cmd put $BACKUPDIRPATH s3://skydevopsbackups/MYSQLBackups/ --recursive &gt; /tmp/s3cmd.log</blockquote>\r\nThese are the folders where all the backups and logs are stored:\r\n\r\n<img class=\" alignright\" src=\"http://i.imgur.com/kjRBqnR.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"422\" height=\"315\" />\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nThis shows that the backup script is create the folder on the current day:\r\n\r\n<img class=\"alignnone\" src=\"http://i.imgur.com/uROjbT3.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"439\" height=\"182\" />\r\n\r\nThe following folder contains the backups. The last 3 backups show that the cronjob is automatically creating backups every hour.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<img class=\"alignnone\" src=\"http://i.imgur.com/cqsRcLK.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"1598\" height=\"534\" />\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n&nbsp;','SQL Backup Scripts','','publish','open','open','','sql-backup-scripts','','','2015-08-20 14:15:44','2015-08-20 14:15:44','',0,'http://52.19.82.119/?p=65',0,'post','',0),(66,2,'2015-08-20 14:15:42','2015-08-20 14:15:42','We are using 2 databases for this system. One is the local database running on LAMP stack for Word Press and we have the RDS cloud MySQL database running on Amazon Web services for the php web application.\r\n\r\n<strong>RDS Backup Script</strong>\r\n\r\nI created a backup script which creates folders using the day\'s date and dumps SQL tables into a file which is named after the time it is created. The script first checks if there is directory for the day. If not it first creates a directory and dumps the SQL data into it. If the directory already exists, it skips creating it and only dumps the data into the directory on the current date. The shell command to dump sql data is following:\r\n<blockquote>mysqldump --user ${USER} -p${PASS} --host ${DBSERVER} --databases ${DATABASE} &gt; $BACKUPDIRPATH$DATE/$FILE</blockquote>\r\n<strong>Logs</strong>\r\n\r\nTo ensure we are able to troubleshoot if the backups are not running. I am saving confirmation of each instance into a log file. The log file writes and confirms that steps are being undertaken.\r\n\r\n<strong>Cronjob</strong>\r\n\r\nCrontab is a linux in-built scheduler which runs scripts on a timely basis. This is the way to automate the script to run every hour. To do this, following commands were used:\r\n<blockquote>crontab -e # To edit crontab file\r\n\r\n0 * * * * /PATH-TO-SCRIPT.sh # insert this to ensure it runs hourly\r\n\r\ncrontab -l # To list the cronjobs currently being executed</blockquote>\r\nScript Screenshot:\r\n\r\n<img class=\"alignnone\" src=\"http://i.imgur.com/HFwB454.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"665\" height=\"403\" />\r\n\r\n<strong>S3 Bucket</strong>\r\n\r\nAll the backups are automatically stored to S3 bucket on Amazon Web Services. To do that, I had to install a s3 tool called s3cmd. This command is used to list,delete,create and put buckets and folders on S3. I used this tool in the script to run automatically once it has created the backups and use the put command to place them.\r\n<blockquote>/home/ec2-user/bin/s3cmd put $BACKUPDIRPATH s3://skydevopsbackups/MYSQLBackups/ --recursive &gt; /tmp/s3cmd.log</blockquote>\r\nThese are the folders where all the backups and logs are stored:\r\n\r\n<img class=\" alignright\" src=\"http://i.imgur.com/kjRBqnR.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"422\" height=\"315\" />\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nThis shows that the backup script is create the folder on the current day:\r\n\r\n<img class=\"alignnone\" src=\"http://i.imgur.com/uROjbT3.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"439\" height=\"182\" />\r\n\r\nThe following folder contains the backups. The last 3 backups show that the cronjob is automatically creating backups every hour.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<img class=\"alignnone\" src=\"http://i.imgur.com/cqsRcLK.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"1598\" height=\"534\" />\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n&nbsp;','SQL Backup Scripts','','inherit','open','open','','65-revision-v1','','','2015-08-20 14:15:42','2015-08-20 14:15:42','',65,'http://52.19.82.119/index.php/2015/08/20/65-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(67,2,'2015-08-20 14:17:03','2015-08-20 14:17:03','We as a team decided to use AWS RDS MYSQL service as it is simple and integrated with Amazon Web Services. AWS allows the option to spread the databases through multiple sites by using the concept of master and slaves. The master copy is the main database instance and the slaves are replicating the database. Hence if the main database goes down, the slave takes over until the master is brought back up again.\r\n\r\nTo create RDS, we have to select RDS service the AWS Dashboard:\r\n\r\n<img class=\"alignnone\" src=\"http://i.imgur.com/i3D034w.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"838\" height=\"514\" />\r\n\r\nClick on Launch DB Instance to create a new instance\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<img class=\"alignnone\" src=\"http://i.imgur.com/yNuwEF8.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"1354\" height=\"494\" />\r\n\r\nThis will prompt the user to select an option to what type of Relation Database System the user would like to select. For this case, I selected MySQL as the developer\'s application requirement was built upon MySQL platform. Once it is selected, the user is prompted with whether to use the Multi AZ deployment service or to be used on one location. I selected MultiAZ deployment as this ensures my database is secure so for instance if my master database located in Ireland data centre site A goes down, the database is replicated to another Site e.g. Site B which will pick up the jobs until the Site A database comes back up.\r\n\r\nOnce that is complete, final step is to configure the instance specifications and settings. This includes, attaching a pre-configured policy, Database Instance Identifier, Master username and password. The next option takes the configurations further to network, security, backups and Database options which includes giving it a name. Most of it is by default pre-configured unless in some circumstances it needs to be changed.\r\n\r\nFinally once the instance is completed, the new instance starts to create itself and appears on the RDS dashboard.\r\n\r\n<img class=\"alignnone\" src=\"http://i.imgur.com/op92mJX.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"1936\" height=\"344\" />\r\n\r\n<strong>MYSQL Monitor</strong>\r\n\r\nTo integrate with the database, I need to have an instance where I can run MySQL utilities which can then be used to connect to the RDS database on amazon using the endpoint. The endpoint is a URL which runs over https and can be found in the Database information:\r\n\r\n<img class=\"alignnone\" src=\"http://i.imgur.com/jPyvXJu.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"1812\" height=\"720\" />\r\n\r\nOnce the endpoint is noted, I launched a new EC2 instance which was used to install mysql locally. Once it was installed, I ran the following command to access mysql:\r\n<blockquote>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\">mysql -u admin -P 3306 -h skydevop2015database.czk330ifgg3j.eu-west-1.rds.amazonaws.com -p**************</p>\r\n</blockquote>\r\nonce in mysql monitor, a script which was provided to us by the developer was executed to create the table and add the datasets into the table. Once the table was inserted, it was time to test it on the php app to ensure that the application is able to select datasets dynamically.\r\n\r\nTo test it, I created a new test EC2 instance which was used to the deploy the application running on LAMP stack except the MYSQL was not really needed as we have a RDS instance running in Amazon Cloud. The only thing that needed modifying was defining the php file to integrate with RDS instance. To do this, I had to change the file useful.php:\r\n\r\n<img class=\"alignnone\" src=\"http://i.imgur.com/IsnYyAB.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"1810\" height=\"258\" />\r\n\r\nOnce this was complete, the webapp was successfully able to access the data from the users table so they could be used to log in.','RDS AWS MYSQL','','inherit','open','open','','35-revision-v1','','','2015-08-20 14:17:03','2015-08-20 14:17:03','',35,'http://52.19.82.119/index.php/2015/08/20/35-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0);
